# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: solar-pv-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] PV solar systems have varying relationships to inverter systems, external grids, battery banks, and other electrical loads.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The central problem addressed by MPPT is that the efficiency of power transfer from the solar cell depends on the amount of available sunlight, shading, solar panel temperature and the load's electrical characteristics.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] As these conditions vary, the load characteristic (impedance) that gives the highest power transfer changes.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The system is optimized when the load characteristic changes to keep power transfer at highest efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] This optimal load characteristic is called the *maximum power point* (MPP).
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] MPPT is the process of adjusting the load characteristic as the conditions change.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Circuits can be designed to present optimal loads to the photovoltaic cells and then convert the voltage, current, or frequency to suit other devices or systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Solar cells' non-linear relationship between temperature and total resistance can be analyzed based on the Current-voltage (I-V) curve and the power-voltage (P-V) curves.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] MPPT samples cell output and applies the proper resistance (load) to obtain maximum power.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] MPPT devices are typically integrated into an electric power converter system that provides voltage or current conversion, filtering, and regulation for driving various loads, including power grids, batteries, or motors.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Solar inverters convert DC power to AC power and may incorporate MPPT.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The power at the MPP (Pmpp) is the product of the MPP voltage (Vmpp) and MPP current (Impp).
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] In general, the P-V curve of a partially shaded solar array can have multiple peaks, and some algorithms can get stuck in a local maximum rather than the global maximum of the curve.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Photovoltaic cells have a complex relationship between their operating environment and the power they produce.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The nonlinear I-V curve characteristic of a given cell in specific temperature and insolation conditions can be functionally characterized by a fill factor (*FF*).
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Fill factor is defined as the ratio of the maximum power from the cell to the product of open circuit voltage *V*oc and short-circuit current *I*sc.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] For most purposes, *FF*, *V*oc, and *I*sc are enough information to give a useful approximate view of the cell's electrical behavior under typical conditions.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] For any given set of conditions, cells have a single operating point where the values of the current (*I*) and voltage (*V*) of the cell allow maximum power output.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] These values correspond to a particular load resistance, which is equal to *V* / *I* as specified by Ohm's law.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] A photovoltaic cell, for the majority of its useful curve, acts as a constant current source.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] However, at a photovoltaic cell's MPP region, its curve has an approximately inverse exponential relationship between current and voltage.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] From basic circuit theory, the power delivered to a device is optimized (MPP) where the derivative (graphically, the slope) *dI/dV* of the I-V curve is equal and opposite the *I/V* ratio (where d*P/dV*=0) and corresponds to the "knee" of the curve.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] A load with resistance *R=V/I* equal to the reciprocal of this value draws the maximum power from the device.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] This is sometimes called the 'characteristic resistance' of the cell.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] This is a dynamic quantity that changes depending on the level of illumination, as well as other factors such as temperature and cell condition.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Lower or higher resistance reduces power output.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Maximum power point trackers utilize control circuits or logic to identify this point.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] If a full power-voltage (P-V) curve is available, then the maximum power point can be obtained using a bisection method.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] When directly connecting a load to cell, the operating point of the panel is rarely at peak power.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The impedance seen by the panel determines its operating point.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Setting the impedance correctly achieves peak power.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Since panels are DC devices, DC-DC converters transform the impedance of one circuit (source) to the other circuit (load).
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Changing the duty ratio of the DC-DC converter changes the impedance (duty ratio) seen by the cell.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The I-V curve of the panel can be considerably affected by atmospheric conditions such as irradiance and temperature.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] MPPT algorithms frequently sample panel voltages and currents, then adjust the duty ratio accordingly.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Microcontrollers implement the algorithms.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Modern implementations often utilize more sophisticated computers for analytics and load forecasting.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Controllers can follow several strategies to optimize power output.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] MPPTs may switch among multiple algorithms as conditions dictate.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] In this method the controller adjusts the voltage from the array by a small amount and measures power; if the power increases, further adjustments in that direction are tried until power no longer increases.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] This is called *perturb and observe* (P&O) and is most common, although this method can cause power output to oscillate.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] It is also referred to as a *hill climbing* method, because it depends on the rise of the curve of power against voltage below the maximum power point, and the fall above that point.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Perturb and observe is the most commonly used method due to its ease of implementation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The Perturb and Observe (P&O) algorithm adjusts the operating voltage of a photovoltaic (PV) system to track the maximum power point (MPP).
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] By periodically perturbing the voltage and observing the resulting change in power, the algorithm decides whether to increase or decrease the operating voltage.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] If the power increases, the perturbation continues in the same direction; otherwise, it reverses direction.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The perturb and observe method may result in top-level efficiency, provided that a proper predictive and adaptive hill climbing strategy is adopted.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] In this method, the controller measures incremental current and voltage changes to predict the effect of a voltage change.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] This method requires more computation in the controller, but can track changing conditions more rapidly than P&O.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] It utilizes the incremental conductance ( $dI/dV$ ) of the photovoltaic array to compute the sign of the change in power with respect to voltage ( $dP/dV$ ).
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The incremental conductance method computes MPP by comparison of the incremental conductance ( $I_{\Delta }/V_{\Delta }$ ) to the array conductance ( $I/V$ ).
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] When these two are the same ( $-I/V=I_{\Delta }/V_{\Delta }$ ), the output voltage is the MPP voltage.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The controller maintains this voltage until the irradiation changes and the process is repeated.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The incremental conductance method is based on the observation that at MPP, $dP/dV=0$ , and that $P=IV$ .
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Setting this equal to zero yields: $dI/dV=-I(V)/V$ .
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Therefore, MPP is achieved when the incremental conductance is equal to the negative of the instantaneous conductance.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The power-voltage curve characteristic shows that: when the voltage is smaller than MPP, $dP/dV>0$ , so $dI/dV>-I/V$ ; when the voltage is bigger than MPP, $dP/dV<0$ or $dI/dV<-I/V$ .
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Thus, a tracker can know where it is on the power-voltage curve by calculating the relation of the change of current/voltage and the current voltage themselves.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The *current sweep* method uses a sweep waveform for the array current such that the I-V characteristic of the PV array is obtained and updated at fixed time intervals.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] MPP voltage can then be computed from the characteristic curve at the same intervals.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] This method estimates the MPP voltage ( $V_{mpp}$ ) by measuring the temperature of the solar module and comparing it against a reference.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Since changes in irradiation levels have a negligible effect on the MPP voltage, its influences may be ignored - the voltage is assumed to vary linearly with temperature.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Both P&O and incremental conductance are examples of "hill climbing" methods that can find the local maximum of the power curve for the array's operating condition, and so provide a true MPP.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] P&O produces power output oscillations around the maximum power point even under steady state irradiance.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Incremental conductance can determine the maximum power point without oscillating.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] It can perform MPPT under rapidly varying irradiation conditions with higher accuracy than P&O.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] However, this method can produce oscillations and can perform erratically under rapidly changing atmospheric conditions.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The sampling frequency is decreased due to the higher complexity of the algorithm compared to P&O.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] In the constant voltage ratio (or "open voltage") method, energy may be lost during the time the current is set to zero.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The approximation of 76% as the $V_{MPP}/V_{OC}$ ratio is not necessarily accurate.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Although simple and low-cost to implement, the interruptions reduce array efficiency and do not ensure finding the actual MPP.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] However, efficiencies of some systems may reach above 95%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Traditional solar inverters perform MPPT for the entire array.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] In such systems the same current, dictated by the inverter, flows through all modules in the string (series).
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Because different modules have different I-V curves and different MPPs (due to manufacturing tolerance, partial shading, etc.) this architecture means some modules will be performing below their MPP, costing efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Instead, MPPTs can be deployed for individual modules, allowing each to operate at peak efficiency despite uneven shading, soiling or electrical mismatch.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Data suggest having one inverter with one MPPT for a project that has identical number of east and west-facing modules presents no disadvantages when compared to having two inverters or one inverter with more than one MPPT.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] At night, an off-grid PV system may use batteries to supply loads.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Although the fully charged battery pack voltage may be close to the PV panel's MPP voltage, this is unlikely to be true at sunrise when the battery is partially discharged.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Charging may begin at a voltage considerably below the PV panel MPP voltage, and an MPPT can resolve this mismatch.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] When the batteries are fully charged and PV production exceeds local loads, an MPPT can no longer operate the panel at its MPP as the excess power has no load to absorb it.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] The MPPT must then shift the PV panel operating point away from the peak power point until production matches demand.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] In a grid-connected system, all delivered power from solar modules is sent to the grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/maximum-power-point-tracking] Therefore, the MPPT in a grid connected system always attempts to operate at MPP.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering policies can vary significantly by country and by state or province: if net metering is available, if and how long banked credits can be retained, and how much the credits are worth (retail/wholesale).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Most net metering laws involve monthly rollover of kWh credits, a small monthly connection fee, require a monthly payment of deficits (i.e. normal electric bill), and annual settlement of any residual credit.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering uses a single, bi-directional meter and can measure the current flowing in two directions.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering can be implemented solely as an accounting procedure, and requires no special metering, or even any prior arrangement or notification.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering is an enabling policy designed to foster private investment in renewable energy.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering originated in the United States, where small wind turbines and solar panels were connected to the electrical grid, and consumers wanted to be able to use the electricity generated at a different time or date from when it was generated.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The first two projects to use net metering were an apartment complex and a solar test house in Massachusetts in 1979.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Minnesota is commonly cited as passing the first net metering law, in 1983, and allowed anyone generating less than 40 kW to either roll over any credit to the next month, or be paid for the excess.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In 2000 this was amended to compensation "at the average retail utility energy rate".
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] This is the simplest and most general interpretation of net metering, and in addition allows small producers to sell electricity at the retail rate.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Utilities in Idaho adopted net metering in 1980, and in Arizona in 1981.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Massachusetts adopted net metering in 1982.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] By 1998, 22 states or utilities therein had adopted net metering.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Two California utilities initially adopted a monthly "net metering" charge, which included a "standby charge", until the Public Utilities Commission (PUC) banned such charges.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In 2005, all U.S. utilities were required to consider adopting rules offering net metering "upon request" by the Energy Policy Act of 2005.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] As of 2013, 43 U.S. states have adopted net metering, as well as utilities in 3 of the remaining states, leaving only 4 states without any established procedures for implementing net metering.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] However, a 2017 study showed that only 3% of U.S. utilities offer full retail compensation for net metering with the remainder offering less than retail rates, having credit expire annually, or some form of indefinite rollover.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering was slow to be adopted in Europe, especially in the United Kingdom, because of confusion over how to address the value added tax (VAT).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Only one utility company in Great Britain offers net metering.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The United Kingdom government is reluctant to introduce the net metering principle because of complications in paying and refunding the value added tax that is payable on electricity, but pilot projects are underway in some areas.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In Canada, some provinces have net metering programs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In the Philippines, Net Metering scheme is governed by Republic Act 9513 (Renewable Energy Act of 2008) and its implementing rules and regulation (IRR).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The implementing body is the Energy Regulatory Commission (ERC) in consultation with the National Renewable Energy Board (NREB).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Unfortunately, the scheme is not a true net metering scheme but in reality a net billing scheme.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] As the Dept of Energy's Net Metering guidelines say, "Net-metering allows customers of Distribution Utilities (DUs) to install an on-site Renewable Energy (RE) facility not exceeding 100 kilowatts (kW) in capacity so they can generate electricity for their own use.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Any electricity generated that is not consumed by the customer is automatically exported to the DU's distribution system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Thus Philippine consumers who generate their own electricity and sell their surplus to the utility are paid what is called the "generation cost" which is often less than 50% of the retail price of electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering is controversial as it affects different interests on the grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] A report prepared by Peter Kind of Energy Infrastructure Advocates for the trade association Edison Electric Institute stated that distributed generation systems, like rooftop solar, present unique challenges to the future of electric utilities.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Utilities in the United States have led a largely unsuccessful campaign to eliminate net metering.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Renewable advocates point out that while distributed solar and other energy efficiency measures do pose a challenge to electric utilities' existing business model, the benefits of distributed generation outweigh the costs, and those benefits are shared by all ratepayers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Grid benefits of private distributed solar investment include reduced need for centralizing power plants and reduced strain on the utility grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] An independent report conducted by the consulting firm Crossborder Energy found that the benefits of California's net metering program outweigh the costs to ratepayers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Those net benefits will amount to more than US$92 million annually upon the completion of the current net metering program.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] A 2012 report on the cost of net metering in the State of California, commissioned by the California Public Utilities Commission (CPUC), showed that those customers without distributed generation systems will pay US$287 in additional costs to use and maintain the grid every year by 2020.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The report also showed the net cost will amount to US$1.1 billion by 2020.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Notably, the same report found that solar customers do pay more on their power bills than what it costs the utility to serve them (Table 5, page 10: average 103% of their cost of service across the three major utilities in 2011).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Many electric utilities state that owners of generation systems do not pay the full cost of service to use the grid, thus shifting their share of the cost onto customers without distributed generation systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Most owners of rooftop solar or other types of distributed generation systems still rely on the grid to receive electricity from utilities at night or when their systems cannot generate sufficient power.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] A 2014 report funded by the Institute for Electric Innovation (which engages in lobbying for the benefit of its member electricity companies) claims that net metering in California produces excessively large subsidies for typical residential rooftop solar photovoltaic (PV) facilities.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] These subsidies must then be paid for by other residential customers, most of whom are less affluent than the rooftop solar PV customers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In addition, the report points out that most of these large subsidies go to the solar leasing companies, which accounted for about 75 percent of the solar PV facilities installed in 2013.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] On a nationwide basis, energy officials have debated replacement programs for net metering for several years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] As of 2018, a few "replicable models" have emerged.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Utility companies have always contended that customers with solar get their bills reduced by too much under net metering, and as a result, that shifts costs for keeping up the grid infrastructure to the rest of the non-solar customers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] "The policy has led to heated state-level debates since 2003 over whether — and how — to construct a successor to the policy," according to Utility Dive.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The key challenge to constructing pricing and rebate schemes in a post-net metering environment is how to compensate rooftop solar customers fairly while not imposing costs on non-solar customers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Experts have said that a good "successor tariff," as the post-net metering policies have been called, is one that supports the growth of distributed energy resources in a way where customers and the grid get benefits from it.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Thirteen states swapped successor tariffs for retail rate net metering programs in 2017.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In 2018, three more states made similar changes.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] For example, compensation in Nevada will go down over time, but today the compensation is at the retail rate (meaning, solar customers who send energy to the grid get compensated at the same rate they pay for electricity).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In Arizona, the new solar rate is ten percent below the retail rate.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The two most common successor tariffs are called "net billing" and "buy-all-sell-all" (BASA).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] "Net billing pays the retail rate for customer-consumed PV generation and a below retail rate for exported generation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] There is considerable confusion between the terms "net metering" and "feed-in tariff" (FIT).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Feed-in tariff: generally above retail, and reduces to retail as the percentage of adopters increases.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Power purchase agreement: Compensation generally below retail, also known as a "Standard Offer Program", can be above retail, particularly in the case of solar, which tends to be generated close to peak demand.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In **market rate net metering** systems the user's energy use is priced dynamically according to some function of wholesale electric prices.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The users' meters are programmed remotely to calculate the value and are read remotely.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering applies such variable pricing to excess power produced by a qualifying system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Market rate metering systems were implemented in California starting in 2006, and under the terms of California's net metering rules will be applicable to qualifying photovoltaic and wind systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Under California law the payback for surplus electricity sent to the grid must be equal to the (variable, in this case) price charged at that time.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] No credit is given for annual surplus production.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Excess generation is a separate issue from net metering, but it is normally dealt with in the same rules, because it can arise.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] If local generation offsets a portion of the demand, net metering is not used.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] If local generation exceeds demand some of the time, for example during the day, net metering is used.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] If local generation exceeds demand for the billing cycle, best practices calls for a perpetual roll over of the kilowatt-hour credits, although some regions have considered having any kWh credits expire after 36 months.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The normal definition of excess generation is annually, although the term is equally applicable monthly.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The treatment of annual excess generation (and monthly) ranges from lost, to compensation at avoided cost, to compensation at retail rate.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Left over kWh credits upon termination of service would ideally be paid at retail rate, from the consumer standpoint, and lost, from the utility standpoint, with avoided cost a minimum compromise.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Some regions allow optional payment for excess annual generation, which allows perpetual roll over or payment, at the customers choice.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Both wind and solar are inherently seasonal, and it is highly likely to use up a surplus later, unless more solar panels or a larger wind turbine have been installed than needed.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering systems can have energy storage integrated, to store some of the power locally (i.e. from the renewable energy source connected to the system) rather than selling everything to the mains electricity grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Often, the batteries used are industrial deep cycle batteries as these last for 10 to 20 years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Other types of batteries with shorter lifespans, like Lead-acid (around 5 years) and Lithium-ion, are also still used.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Finally, nickel-iron batteries last the longest with a lifespan of up to 40 years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] A 2017 study of solar panels with battery storage indicated an 8 to 14 percent extra consumption of electricity from charging and discharging batteries.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The financial differences are very substantial.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In Victoria, from 2009, householders were paid 60 cents for every excess kilowatt hour of energy fed into the state electricity grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] This was around three times the retail price for electricity at that time.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] However, subsequent state governments reduced the feed-in in several updates, until in 2016 the feed-in is as low as 5 cents per kilowatt hour.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In Queensland starting in 2008, the Solar Bonus Scheme pays 44 cents for every excess kilowatt hour of energy fed into the state electricity grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] This is around three times the current retail price for electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] However, from 2012, the Queensland feed in tariff has been reduced to 6-10 cents per kilowatt hour depending on which electricity retailer the customer has signed up with.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Australian smart grid technologist, Steve Hoy, originated the opposing concept of "True Zero", as opposed to "Net Zero", to express the emerging capability to trace electricity through net metering.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The meter allows consumers to trace their electricity to the source, making clean energy more accessible to everyone.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Ontario allows net metering for systems up to 500 kW, however credits can only be carried for 12 consecutive months.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Should a consumer establish a credit where they generate more than they consume for 8 months and use up the credits in the 10th month, then the 12-month period begins again from the date that the next credit is shown on an invoice.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Any unused credits remaining at the end of 12 consecutive months of a consumer being in a credit situation are cleared at the end of that billing.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Areas of British Columbia serviced by BC Hydro are allowed net metering for up to 100 kW.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] At each annual anniversary on March 1 the customer is paid a market price, calculated as daily average mid-Columbia price for a previous year.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] FortisBC which serves an area in South Central BC also allows net-metering for up to 50 kW.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Customers are paid their existing retail rate for any net energy they produce.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The City of New Westminster, which has its own electrical utility, also allows net metering.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] New Brunswick allows net metering for installations up to 100 kW.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Credits from excess generated power can be carried over until March at which time any excess credits are lost.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] SaskPower allows net metering for installations up to 100 kW.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Credits from excess generated power can be carried over until the customer's annual anniversary date, at which time any excess credits are lost.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In Nova Scotia, in 2015, 43 residences and businesses began using solar panels for electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] These customers’ solar systems are net metered.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] As of 2024, 7000 Nova Scotians had installed solar.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] As of 31 December 2024, there were 45 active commercial net metering generators totalling 4.1 MW, and 11 102 legacy net metering customers (including 58 with wind, 1with hydro, and 6 six "other/combination") with a nameplate capacity of 97.7 MW.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] This was over double the projection of 39 MW published in 2020 for 2025.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Denmark established net-metering for privately owned PV systems in mid-1998 for a pilot-period of four years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In 2002 the net-metering scheme was extended another four years up to end of 2006.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net-metering has proved to be a cheap, easy to administer and effective way of stimulating the deployment of PV in Denmark; however the relative short time window of the arrangement has so far prevented it from reaching its full potential.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] During the political negotiations in the fall of 2005 the net-metering for privately owned PV systems was made permanent.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The Netherlands has net-metering since 2004.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Initially there was a limit of 3000 kWh per year.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Later this limit was increased to 5000 kWh.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The limit was removed altogether on January 1, 2014.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Italy offers a support scheme, mixing net-metering and a well segmented premium FiT.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Slovenia has annual net-metering since January 2016 for up to 11 kVA.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In a calendar year up to 10 MVA can be installed in the country.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In 2010, Spain, net-metering has been proposed by the *Asociación de la Industria Fotovoltaica* (ASIF) to promote renewable electricity, without requiring additional economic support.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net-metering for privately owned systems will be established in 2019, after Royal Decree 244/2019 was accepted by the government on April 5.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Some form of net metering is now proposed by *Électricité de France*.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] According to their website, energy produced by home-owners is bought at a higher price than what is charged as consumers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Hence, some recommend to sell all energy produced, and buy back all energy needed at a lower price.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The price has been fixed for 20 years by the government.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Ireland is planning to implement a net metering system, under the "Micro-generation Support Scheme".
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Under the proposed scheme, micro-generators can sell 30% of the excess electricity they produce and export it back to the grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The price that electricity will be sold at is being formulated during the consultation process.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Poland has introduced net metering for private and commercial renewable energy sources of up to 50 kW in 2015.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Under this legislation energy sent to grid must be used within one year from feed-in, otherwise it is considered as lost.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The amount of energy that was exported and can be taken back by the user is subtracted by 20% for installations up to 10 kW, or by 30% for installations up to 50 kW.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] This legislation guarantees that this net metering policy will be kept for a minimum of 15 years from the moment of registering renewable energy source.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] This legislation together with government subsidies for microgeneration created a substantial boost in installations of PV systems in Poland.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Portugal has a very limited form of "net-metering" that is constrained to 15 minute periods where the excess injected in the grid is not compensated when above the consumption from the grid within each 15 minute period.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Only the injected energy up to the consumed energy within the same 15 minute period is netted out of the final monthly bill.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In fact the old analog electricity meters that would allow for true net-metering are immediately replaced when a consumer installs solar pv.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Almost every state in India has implemented net-metering, wherein, the consumers are allowed to sell the surplus energy generated by their solar system to the grid and get compensated for the same.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] However, the net-metering policy is not common throughout the country and varies from state to state.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] To avail of net-metering in the country, the consumer is required to submit an application with the local electricity distribution company along with the planned rooftop solar project and requisite fee.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The distribution company reviews the application and the feasibility of the solar project, which is either approved or rejected.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] If approved, another application for registration of the rooftop is submitted to the distribution company.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] An agreement is signed between the consumer and the company, and the net-meter is installed.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The Indian states of Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh have started the implementation of net metering, and the policy was announced by the respective state electricity boards in 2014.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] After review and inspection by the electricity board, a bidirectional meter is installed.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Applications are taken up for up to 30% of the distribution transformer capacity on a first-come, first-served basis and technical feasibility.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Since September 2015, Maharashtra state (MERC) has also had a net metering policy and consumers have started installation of Solar Rooftop Grid Tie Net metering systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] MERC Policy allows up to 40% transformer capacity to be on Solar net metering.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The various DISCOMs in Maharashtra namely MSEDCL, Tata, Reliance and Torrent Power are expected to support net metering.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] As of now MSEDCL does not use the TOD (Time of The Day differential) charging tariffs for residential consumers and net metering.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Export and import units are considered at par for calculating Net Units and bill amount.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering is a policy by many states in the United States designed to help the adoption of renewable energy.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering was pioneered in the United States as a way to allow solar and wind to provide electricity whenever available and allow use of that electricity whenever it was needed, beginning with utilities in Idaho in 1980, and in Arizona in 1981.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In 1983, Minnesota passed the first state net metering law.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] As of March 2015, 44 states and Washington, D.C. have developed mandatory net metering rules for at least some utilities.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] However, although the states' rules are clear, few utilities actually compensate at full retail rates.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Net metering policies are determined by states, which have set policies varying on a number of key dimensions.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The Energy Policy Act of 2005 required state electricity regulators to "consider" (but not necessarily implement) rules that mandate public electric utilities make net metering available to their customers upon request.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Several legislative bills have been proposed to institute a federal standard limit on net metering.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] 729, which sets a net metering cap at 2% of forecasted aggregate customer peak demand, to H.R.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] 1945, which has no aggregate cap, but does limit residential users to 10 kW, a low limit compared to many states, such as New Mexico, with an 80,000 kW limit, or states such as Arizona, Colorado, New Jersey, and Ohio, which limit as a percentage of load.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Under this arrangement, two uni-directional meters are installed—one records electricity drawn from the grid, and the other records excess electricity generated and fed into the grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The user pays retail rate for the electricity they use, and the power provider purchases their excess generation at its avoided cost (wholesale rate).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] There may be a significant difference between the retail rate the user pays and the power provider's avoided cost.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Some jurisdictions, such as Germany, Spain, the province of Ontario in Canada, and some states in the United States, compensate the generated electricity at a fixed rate, in a scheme called feed-in tariff (FIT).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] With the FIT, customers get paid for any electricity they generate from renewable energy on their premises.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The actual electricity being generated is counted on a separate meter, not just the surplus they feed to the grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Germany once paid several times the retail rate for solar but has reduced the rates drastically while actual installation of solar has grown exponentially at the same time due to reduced cost of solar installations.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Wind energy, in contrast, only receives around a half of the domestic retail rate, because the German system pays what each source costs (including a reasonable profit margin).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Another method of producing power to the grid is through **virtual net metering** (also called peer-to-peer (P2P) energy trading, wheeling and sometimes local energy trading).
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Peer-to-peer energy trading is a novel paradigm of power system operation, where sellers can generate their own energy in dwellings, offices and factories, and share it with each other locally.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Several companies offering virtual net metering use blockchain technology.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Sources that produce direct current, such as solar panels, must be coupled with an electrical inverter to convert the output to alternating current for use with conventional appliances.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] The phase of the outgoing power must be synchronized with the grid, and a mechanism must be included to disconnect the feed in the event of grid failure.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] This is for safety – for example, workers repairing downed power lines must be protected from "downstream" sources, in addition to being disconnected from the main "upstream" distribution grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Although a small generator lacks the power to energize a loaded line, this can happen if the line is isolated from other loads.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] Solar inverters are designed for safety – while one inverter could not energize a line, a thousand might.
[src:solar-pv-systems/net-metering] In addition, electrical workers are trained to treat every line as though it was live, even when they know it should be safe.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A **photovoltaic system**, also called a **PV system** or **solar power system**, is an electric power system designed to supply usable solar power by means of photovoltaics.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] It consists of an arrangement of several components, including solar panels to absorb and convert sunlight into electricity, a solar inverter to convert the output from direct to alternating current, as well as mounting, cabling, and other electrical accessories to set up a working system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Many utility-scale PV systems use tracking systems that follow the sun's daily path across the sky to generate more electricity than fixed-mounted systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Photovoltaic systems convert light directly into electricity and are not to be confused with other solar technologies, such as concentrated solar power or solar thermal, used for heating and cooling.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A **solar array** only encompasses the solar panels, the visible part of the PV system, and does not include all the other hardware, often summarized as the balance of system (BOS).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] PV systems range from small, rooftop-mounted or building-integrated systems with capacities ranging from a few to several tens of kilowatts to large, utility-scale power stations of hundreds of megawatts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Nowadays, off-grid or stand-alone systems account for a small portion of the market.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Operating silently and without any moving parts or air pollution, PV systems have evolved from niche market applications into a mature technology used for mainstream electricity generation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Due to the growth of photovoltaics, prices for PV systems have rapidly declined since their introduction; however, they vary by market and the size of the system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Nowadays, solar PV modules account for less than half of the system's overall cost, leaving the rest to the remaining BOS components and to soft costs, which include customer acquisition, permitting, inspection and interconnection, installation labor, and financing costs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A photovoltaic system converts the Sun's radiation, in the form of light, into usable electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] It comprises the solar array and the balance of system components.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Other distinctions may include, systems with microinverters vs. central inverter, systems using crystalline silicon vs. thin-film technology, and systems with modules.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] About 99 percent of all European and 90 percent of all US solar power systems are connected to the electrical grid, while off-grid systems are somewhat more common in Australia and South Korea.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] This may change, as government incentives for distributed energy storage are implemented and investments in storage solutions gradually become economically viable for small systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In the UK, the number of commercial systems using battery storage is gradually increasing as a result of grid constraints preventing feedback of unused electricity into the grid as well as increased electricity costs resulting in improved economics.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A typical residential solar array is rack-mounted on the roof, rather than integrated into the roof or facade of the building, which is significantly more expensive.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Utility-scale solar power stations are ground-mounted, with fixed tilted solar panels rather than using expensive tracking devices.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Crystalline silicon is the predominant material used in 90 percent of worldwide produced solar modules, while its rival thin-film has lost market-share.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] About 70 percent of all solar cells and modules are produced in China and Taiwan, only 5 percent by European and US manufacturers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Driven by advances in technology and increases in manufacturing scale and sophistication, the cost of photovoltaics is declining continuously.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] There are several million PV systems distributed all over the world, mostly in Europe, with 1.4 million systems in Germany alone – as well as North America with 440,000 systems in the United States.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The energy conversion efficiency of a conventional solar module increased from 15 to 20 percent since 2004 and a PV system recoups the energy needed for its manufacture in about 2 years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In exceptionally irradiated locations, or when thin-film technology is used, the so-called energy payback time decreases to one year or less.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Net metering and financial incentives, such as preferential feed-in tariffs for solar-generated electricity, have also greatly supported installations of PV systems in many countries.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The levelised cost of electricity from large-scale PV systems has become competitive with conventional electricity sources in an expanding list of geographic regions, and grid parity has been achieved in about 30 countries.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] As of 2015, the fast-growing global PV market is rapidly approaching the 200 GW mark – about 40 times the installed capacity in 2006.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] These systems currently contribute about 1 percent to worldwide electricity generation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Top installers of PV systems in terms of capacity are currently China, Japan and the United States, while half of the world's capacity is installed in Europe, with Germany and Italy supplying 7–8% of their respective domestic electricity consumption with solar PV.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The International Energy Agency expects solar power to become the world's largest source of electricity by 2050, with solar photovoltaics and concentrated solar thermal contributing 16% and 11% to the global demand, respectively.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A grid connected system is connected to a larger independent grid (typically the public electricity grid) and feeds energy directly into the grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] This energy may be shared by a residential or commercial building before or after the revenue measurement point, depending on whether the credited energy production is calculated independently of the customer's energy consumption (feed-in tariff) or only on the difference of energy (net metering).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] These systems vary in size from residential (2–10 kWp) to solar power stations (up to tens of MWp).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] This is a form of decentralized electricity generation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Feeding electricity into the grid requires the transformation of DC into AC by a special, synchronizing grid-tie inverter.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In kilowatt-sized installations the DC side system voltage is as high as permitted (typically 1000 V except US residential 600 V) to limit ohmic losses.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Most modules (60 or 72 crystalline silicon cells) generate 160 W to 300 W at 36 volts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] It is sometimes necessary or desirable to connect the modules partially in parallel rather than all in series.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] An individual set of modules connected in series is known as a 'string'.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A set of series-connected "strings" is known as an "array".
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Photovoltaic systems are generally categorized into three distinct market segments: residential rooftop, commercial rooftop, and ground-mount utility-scale systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Their capacities range from a few kilowatts to hundreds of megawatts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A typical residential system is around 10 kilowatts and mounted on a sloped roof, while commercial systems may reach a megawatt-scale and are generally installed on low-slope or even flat roofs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Although rooftop mounted systems are small and have a higher cost per watt than large utility-scale installations, they account for the largest share in the market.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] There is, however, a growing trend towards bigger utility-scale power plants, especially in the "sunbelt" region of the planet.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Large utility-scale solar parks or farms are power stations and capable of providing an energy supply to large numbers of consumers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Generated electricity is fed into the transmission grid powered by central generation plants (grid-connected or grid-tied plant), or combined with one, or many, domestic electricity generators to feed into a small electrical grid (hybrid plant).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In rare cases generated electricity is stored or used directly by island/standalone plant.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] PV systems are generally designed in order to ensure the highest energy yield for a given investment.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Some large photovoltaic power stations such as Solar Star, Waldpolenz Solar Park and Topaz Solar Farm cover tens or hundreds of hectares and have power outputs up to hundreds of megawatts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A small PV system is capable of providing enough AC electricity to power a single home, or an isolated device in the form of AC or DC electric.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In 2013, rooftop systems accounted for 60 percent of worldwide installations.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] However, there is a trend away from rooftop and towards utility-scale PV systems, as the focus of new PV installations is also shifting from Europe to countries in the sunbelt region of the planet where opposition to ground-mounted solar farms is less accentuated.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Portable and mobile PV systems provide electrical power independent of utility connections, for "off the grid" operation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Such systems are so commonly used on recreational vehicles and boats that there are retailers specializing in these applications and products specifically targeted to them.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Since recreational vehicles (RV) normally carry batteries and operate lighting and other systems on nominally 12-volt DC power, RV systems normally operate in a voltage range that can charge 12-volt batteries directly, so addition of a PV system requires only panels, a charge controller, and wiring.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Solar systems on recreation vehicles are usually constrained in wattage by the physical size of the RV's roof space.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In urban and suburban areas, photovoltaic arrays are often used on rooftops to supplement power use; often the building will have a connection to the power grid, in which case the energy produced by the PV array can be sold back to the utility in some sort of net metering agreement.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Some utilities use the rooftops of commercial customers and telephone poles to support their use of PV panels.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Solar trees are arrays that, as the name implies, mimic the look of trees, provide shade, and at night can function as street lights.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Uncertainties in revenue over time relate mostly to the evaluation of the solar resource and to the performance of the system itself.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Identifying and reacting to manageable losses is critical for revenue and O&M efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Monitoring of array performance may be part of contractual agreements between the array owner, the builder, and the utility purchasing the energy produced.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A method to create "synthetic days" using readily available weather data and verification using the Open Solar Outdoors Test Field make it possible to predict photovoltaic systems performance with high degrees of accuracy.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] This method can be used to then determine loss mechanisms on a local scale – such as those from snow or the effects of surface coatings (e.g. hydrophobic or hydrophilic) on soiling or snow losses.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] (Although in heavy snow environments with severe ground interference can result in annual losses from snow of 30%.) Access to the Internet has allowed a further improvement in energy monitoring and communication.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Dedicated systems are available from a number of vendors.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For solar PV systems that use microinverters (panel-level DC to AC conversion), module power data is automatically provided.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Some systems allow setting performance alerts that trigger phone/email/text warnings when limits are reached.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] These solutions provide data for the system owner and the installer.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Installers are able to remotely monitor multiple installations, and see at-a-glance the status of their entire installed base.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A photovoltaic system for residential, commercial, or industrial energy supply consists of the solar array and a number of components often summarized as the balance of system (BOS).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] This term is synonymous with "Balance of plant" q.v.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In addition, a CPV system requires optical lenses or mirrors and sometimes a cooling system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The terms "solar array" and "PV system" are often incorrectly used interchangeably, despite the fact that the solar array does not encompass the entire system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Moreover, "solar panel" is often used as a synonym for "solar module", although a panel consists of a string of several modules.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The term "solar system" is also an often used misnomer for a PV system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The building blocks of a photovoltaic system are solar cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A solar cell is the electrical device that can directly convert photons energy into electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Conventional c-Si solar cells, normally wired in series, are encapsulated in a solar module to protect them from the weather.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The module consists of a tempered glass as cover, a soft and flexible encapsulant, a rear backsheet made of a weathering and fire-resistant material and an aluminium frame around the outer edge.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Electrically connected and mounted on a supporting structure, solar modules build a string of modules, often called solar panel.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A solar array consists of one or many such panels.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A photovoltaic array, or solar array, is a linked collection of solar modules.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The power that one module can produce is seldom enough to meet requirements of a home or a business, so the modules are linked together to form an array.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Most PV arrays use an inverter to convert the DC power produced by the modules into alternating current that can power lights, motors, and other loads.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The modules in a PV array are usually first connected in series to obtain the desired voltage; the individual strings are then connected in parallel to allow the system to produce more current.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Solar panels are typically measured under STC (standard test conditions) or PTC (PVUSA test conditions), in watts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Typical panel ratings range from less than 100 watts to over 400 watts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The array rating consists of a summation of the panel ratings, in watts, kilowatts, or megawatts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A typical 150 watt PV module is about a square meter in size.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Such a module may be expected to produce 0.75 kilowatt-hour (kWh) every day, on average, after taking into account the weather and the latitude, for an insolation of 5 sun hours/day.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Module output degrades faster at increased temperature.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Allowing ambient air to flow over, and if possible behind, PV modules reduces this problem, as the airflow tend to reduce the operating temperature and, as consequence, increase the module efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Effective module lives are typically 25 years or more.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The payback period for an investment in a PV solar installation varies greatly and is typically less useful than a calculation of return on investment.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] While it is typically calculated to be between 10 and 20 years, the financial payback period can be far shorter with incentives.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The temperature effect on photovoltaic modules is usually quantified by means of some coefficients relating the variations of the open‐circuit voltage, of the short‐circuit current, and of the maximum power to temperature changes.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In this paper, comprehensive experimental guidelines to estimate the temperature coefficients.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Due to the low voltage of an individual solar cell (typically ca.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] 0.5V), several cells are wired *(see Copper in renewable energy#Solar photovoltaic power generation)* in series in the manufacture of a "laminate".
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The laminate is assembled into a protective weatherproof enclosure, thus making a photovoltaic module or solar panel.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Modules may then be strung together into a photovoltaic array.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In 2012, solar panels available for consumers had an efficiency of up to about 17%, while commercially available panels can go as far as 27%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] By concentrating the sunlight it is possible to achieve higher efficiencies.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A group from The Fraunhofer Institute for Solar Energy Systems has created a cell that can reach 44.7% efficiency using the equivalent of "297 suns".
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Photovoltaic cell electrical output is extremely sensitive to shading (the so-called "Christmas light effect").
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] When even a small portion of a cell or of a module or array of cells in parallel is shaded, with the remainder in sunlight, the output falls dramatically due to internal 'short-circuiting' (the electrons reversing course through the shaded portion).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] When connected in series, the current drawn from a string of cells is no greater than the normally small current that can flow through the shaded cell, so the current (and therefore power) developed by the string is limited.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] If the external load is of low enough impedance, there may be enough voltage available from the other cells in a string to force more current through the shaded cell by breaking down the junction.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] This breakdown voltage in common cells is between 10 and 30 volts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Instead of adding to the power produced by the panel, the shaded cell absorbs power, turning it into heat.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Since the reverse voltage of a shaded cell is much greater than the forward voltage of an illuminated cell, one shaded cell can absorb the power of many other cells in the string, disproportionately affecting panel output.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For example, a shaded cell may drop 8 volts, instead of adding 0.5 volts, at a high current level, thereby absorbing the power produced by 16 other cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] It is thus important that a PV installation not be shaded by trees or other obstructions.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] There are techniques to mitigate the losses with diodes, but these techniques also entail losses.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Several methods have been developed to determine shading losses from trees to PV systems over both large regions using LiDAR, but also at an individual system level using 3D modeling software.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Most modules have bypass diodes between each cell or string of cells that minimize the effects of shading and only lose the power that the shaded portion of the array would have supplied, as well as the power dissipated in the diodes.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The main job of the bypass diode is to eliminate hot spots that form on cells that can cause further damage to the array, and cause fires.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Sunlight can be absorbed by dust, snow, or other impurities at the surface of the module (collectively referred to as soiling).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Soiling reduces the light that strikes the cells, which in turn reduces the power output of the PV system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Soiling losses aggregate over time, and can become large without adequate cleaning.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In 2018, the global annual energy loss due to soiling was estimated to at least 3–4%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] However, soiling losses vary significantly from region to region, and within regions.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Maintaining a clean module surface will increase output performance over the life of the PV system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In one study performed in a snow-rich area (Ontario), cleaning flat mounted solar panels after 15 months increased their output by almost 100%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] However, 5° tilted arrays were adequately cleaned by rainwater.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In many cases, especially in arid regions, or in locations in close proximity to deserts, roads, industry, or agriculture, regular cleaning of the solar panels is cost-effective.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In 2018, the estimated soiling-induced revenue loss was estimated to between 5 and 7 billion euros.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The long‐term reliability of photovoltaic modules is crucial to ensure the technical and economic viability of PV as a successful energy source.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The analysis of degradation mechanisms of PV modules is key to ensure current lifetimes exceeding 25 years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Solar insolation is made up of direct, diffuse, and reflected radiation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The absorption factor of a PV cell is defined as the fraction of incident solar irradiance that is absorbed by the cell.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] When the sun is at the zenith on a cloudless day, the power of the sun is about 1 kW/m2, on the Earth's surface, to a plane that is perpendicular to the sun's rays.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] As such, PV arrays can track the sun through each day to greatly enhance energy collection.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] However, tracking devices add cost, and require maintenance, so it is more common for PV arrays to have fixed mounts that tilt the array and face due south in the northern hemisphere or due north in the southern hemisphere.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The tilt angle from horizontal can be varied for season, but if fixed, should be set to give optimal array output during the peak electrical demand portion of a typical year for a stand-alone system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] This optimal module tilt angle is not necessarily identical to the tilt angle for maximum annual array energy output.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The optimization of the photovoltaic system for a specific environment can be complicated as issues of solar flux, soiling, and snow losses should be taken into effect.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In addition, later work has shown that spectral effects can play a role in optimal photovoltaic material selection.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For example, the spectrum of the albedo of the surroundings can play a significant role in output depending on the surface around the photovoltaic system and the type of solar cell material.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A typical 1 kW photovoltaic installation in Australia or the southern latitudes of Europe or United States, may produce 3.5–5 kWh per day, dependent on location, orientation, tilt, insolation and other factors.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In the Sahara desert, with less cloud cover and a better solar angle, one could ideally obtain closer to 8.3 kWh/m2/day provided the nearly ever present wind would not blow sand onto the units.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The area of the Sahara desert is over 9 million km2.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] 90,600 km2, or about 1%, could generate as much electricity as all of the world's power plants combined.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Modules are assembled into arrays on some kind of mounting system, which may be classified as ground mount, roof mount or pole mount.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For solar parks a large rack is mounted on the ground, and the modules mounted on the rack.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For buildings, many different racks have been devised for pitched roofs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For flat roofs, racks, bins and building integrated solutions are used.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Solar panel racks mounted on top of poles can be stationary or moving, see Trackers below.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Side-of-pole mounts are suitable for situations where a pole has something else mounted at its top, such as a light fixture or an antenna.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Pole mounting raises what would otherwise be a ground mounted array above weed shadows and livestock, and may satisfy electrical code requirements regarding inaccessibility of exposed wiring.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Pole mounted panels are open to more cooling air on their underside, which increases performance.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A multiplicity of pole top racks can be formed into a parking carport or other shade structure.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A rack which does not follow the sun from left to right may allow seasonal adjustment up or down.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Due to their outdoor usage, solar cables are designed to be resistant against UV radiation and extremely high temperature fluctuations and are generally unaffected by the weather.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A solar cable is the interconnection cable used in photovoltaic power generation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Solar cables interconnect solar panels and other electrical components of a photovoltaic system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Solar cables are designed to be UV resistant and weather resistant.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] They can be used within a large temperature range.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Specific performance requirements for material used for wiring a solar panel installation are given in national and local electrical codes which regulate electrical installations in an area.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] General features required for solar cables are resistance to ultraviolet light, weather, temperature extremes of the area and insulation suitable for the voltage class of the equipment.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Different jurisdictions will have specific rules regarding grounding (earthing) of solar power installations for electric shock protection and lightning protection.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A solar tracking system tilts a solar panel throughout the day.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Depending on the type of tracking system, the panel is either aimed directly at the Sun or the brightest area of a partly clouded sky.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Trackers greatly enhance early morning and late afternoon performance, increasing the total amount of power produced by a system by about 20–25% for a single axis tracker and about 30% or more for a dual axis tracker, depending on latitude.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Trackers are effective in regions that receive a large portion of sunlight directly.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In diffuse light (i.e. under cloud or fog), tracking has little or no value.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Because most concentrated photovoltaics systems are very sensitive to the sunlight's angle, tracking systems allow them to produce useful power for more than a brief period each day.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Tracking systems improve performance for two main reasons.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] First, when a solar panel is perpendicular to the sunlight, it receives more light on its surface than if it were angled.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Second, direct light is used more efficiently than angled light.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Special anti-reflective coatings can improve solar panel efficiency for direct and angled light, somewhat reducing the benefit of tracking.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Trackers and sensors to optimise the performance are often seen as optional, but they can increase viable output by up to 45%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Arrays that approach or exceed one megawatt often use solar trackers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Considering clouds, and the fact that most of the world is not on the equator, and that the sun sets in the evening, the correct measure of solar power is insolation – the average number of kilowatt-hours per square meter per day.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For the weather and latitudes of the United States and Europe, typical insolation ranges from 2.26 kWh/m2/day in northern climes to 5.61 kWh/m2/day in the sunniest regions.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For large systems, the energy gained by using tracking systems can outweigh the added complexity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For very large systems, the added maintenance of tracking is a substantial detriment.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Tracking is not required for flat panel and low-concentration photovoltaic systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For high-concentration photovoltaic systems, dual axis tracking is a necessity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Pricing trends affect the balance between adding more stationary solar panels versus having fewer panels that track.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] As pricing, reliability and performance of single-axis trackers have improved, the systems have been installed in an increasing percentage of utility-scale projects.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] According to data from WoodMackenzie/GTM Research, global solar tracker shipments hit a record 14.5 gigawatts in 2017.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] This represents growth of 32 percent year-over-year, with similar or greater growth projected as large-scale solar deployment accelerates.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Systems designed to deliver alternating current (AC), such as grid-connected applications need an inverter to convert the direct current (DC) from the solar modules to AC.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Grid connected inverters must supply AC electricity in sinusoidal form, synchronized to the grid frequency, limit feed in voltage to no higher than the grid voltage and disconnect from the grid if the grid voltage is turned off.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Islanding inverters need only produce regulated voltages and frequencies in a sinusoidal waveshape as no synchronisation or co-ordination with grid supplies is required.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A solar inverter may connect to a string of solar panels.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In some installations a solar micro-inverter is connected at each solar panel.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For safety reasons a circuit breaker is provided both on the AC and DC side to enable maintenance.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] AC output may be connected through an electricity meter into the public grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The number of modules in the system determines the total DC watts capable of being generated by the solar array; however, the inverter ultimately governs the amount of AC watts that can be distributed for consumption.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] For example, a PV system comprising 11 kilowatts DC (kWDC) worth of PV modules, paired with one 10-kilowatt AC (kWAC) inverter, will be limited to the inverter's output of 10 kW.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] As of 2019, conversion efficiency for state-of-the-art converters reached more than 98 percent.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] While string inverters are used in residential to medium-sized commercial PV systems, central inverters cover the large commercial and utility-scale market.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Market-share for central and string inverters are about 44 percent and 52 percent, respectively, with less than 1 percent for micro-inverters.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Maximum power point tracking (MPPT) is a technique that grid connected inverters use to get the maximum possible power from the photovoltaic array.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In order to do so, the inverter's MPPT system digitally samples the solar array's ever changing power output and applies the proper impedance to find the optimal *maximum power point*.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Anti-islanding is a protection mechanism to immediately shut down the inverter, preventing it from generating AC power when the connection to the load no longer exists.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] This happens, for example, in the case of a blackout.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Without this protection, the supply line would become an "island" with power surrounded by a "sea" of unpowered lines, as the solar array continues to deliver DC power during the power outage.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Islanding is a hazard to utility workers, who may not realize that an AC circuit is still powered, and it may prevent automatic re-connection of devices.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Anti-Islanding feature is not required for complete Off-Grid Systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Although still expensive, PV systems increasingly use rechargeable batteries to store a surplus to be later used at night.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Batteries used for grid-storage also stabilize the electrical grid by leveling out peak loads, and play an important role in a smart grid, as they can charge during periods of low demand and feed their stored energy into the grid when demand is high.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Common battery technologies used in today's PV systems include the valve regulated lead-acid battery – a modified version of the conventional lead–acid battery – nickel–cadmium and lithium-ion batteries.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Compared to the other types, lead-acid batteries have a shorter lifetime and lower energy density.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In 2015, Tesla Motors launched the Powerwall, a rechargeable lithium-ion battery with the aim to revolutionize energy consumption.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] PV systems with an integrated battery solution also need a charge controller, as the varying voltage and current from the solar array requires constant adjustment to prevent damage from overcharging.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Basic charge controllers may simply turn the PV panels on and off, or may meter out pulses of energy as needed, a strategy called PWM or pulse-width modulation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] More advanced charge controllers will incorporate MPPT logic into their battery charging algorithms.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Charge controllers may also divert energy to some purpose other than battery charging.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Rather than simply shut off the free PV energy when not needed, a user may choose to heat air or water once the battery is full.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The metering must be able to accumulate energy units in both directions, or two meters must be used.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Many meters accumulate bidirectionally, some systems use two meters, but a unidirectional meter (with detent) will not accumulate energy from any resultant feed into the grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] In some countries, for installations over 30 kWp a frequency and a voltage monitor with disconnection of all phases is required.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] This is done where more solar power is being generated than can be accommodated by the utility, and the excess can not either be exported or stored.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Grid operators historically have needed to provide transmission lines and generation capacity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] This is normally hydro-storage, but other means of storage are used.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Initially storage was used so that baseload generators could operate at full output.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] With variable renewable energy, storage is needed to allow power generation whenever it is available, and consumption whenever needed.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] The two variables a grid operator has are storing electricity for *when* it is needed, or transmitting it to *where* it is needed.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] If both of those fail, installations over 30kWp can automatically shut down, although in practice all inverters maintain voltage regulation and stop supplying power if the load is inadequate.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Grid operators have the option of curtailing excess generation from large systems, although this is more commonly done with wind power than solar power, and results in a substantial loss of revenue.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Three-phase inverters have the unique option of supplying reactive power which can be advantageous in matching load requirements.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Photovoltaic systems need to be monitored to detect breakdown and optimize operation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] There are several photovoltaic monitoring strategies depending on the output of the installation and its nature.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Monitoring can be performed on site or remotely.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] It can measure production only, retrieve all the data from the inverter or retrieve all of the data from the communicating equipment (probes, meters, etc.).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Monitoring tools can be dedicated to supervision only or offer additional functions.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Individual inverters and battery charge controllers may include monitoring using manufacturer specific protocols and software.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Energy metering of an inverter may be of limited accuracy and not suitable for revenue metering purposes.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] A third-party data acquisition system can monitor multiple inverters, using the inverter manufacturer's protocols, and also acquire weather-related information.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Independent smart meters may measure the total energy production of a PV array system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Separate measures such as satellite image analysis or a solar radiation meter (a pyranometer) can be used to estimate total insolation for comparison.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Data collected from a monitoring system can be displayed remotely over the World Wide Web, such as OSOTF.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] Knowing the annual energy consumption in Kwh $E_{d}$ of an institution or a family, for example of 2300Kwh, legible in its electricity bill, it is possible to calculate the number of photovoltaic panels necessary to satisfy its energy needs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p01] On average, each family manages to consume 30% of energy directly from the photovoltaic.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] This section includes systems that are either highly specialized and uncommon or still an emerging new technology with limited significance.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] However, standalone or off-grid systems take a special place.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] They were the most common type of systems during the 1980s and 1990s, when PV technology was still very expensive and a pure niche market of small scale applications.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Only in places where no electrical grid was available, they were economically viable.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Although new stand-alone systems are still being deployed all around the world, their contribution to the overall installed photovoltaic capacity is decreasing.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In Europe, off-grid systems account for 1 percent of installed capacity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In the United States, they account for about 10 percent.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Off-grid systems are still common in Australia and South Korea, and in many developing countries.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Concentrator photovoltaics (CPV) and *high concentrator photovoltaic* (HCPV) systems use optical lenses or curved mirrors to concentrate sunlight onto small but highly efficient solar cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Besides concentrating optics, CPV systems sometime use solar trackers and cooling systems and are more expensive.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Especially HCPV systems are best suited in location with high solar irradiance, concentrating sunlight up to 400 times or more, with efficiencies of 24–28 percent, exceeding those of regular systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Various designs of systems are commercially available but not very common.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] However, ongoing research and development is taking place.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] CPV is often confused with CSP (concentrated solar power) that does not use photovoltaics.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Both technologies favor locations that receive much sunlight and directly compete with each other.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] A hybrid system combines PV with other forms of generation, usually a diesel generator.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The other form of generation may be a type able to modulate power output as a function of demand.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] However more than one renewable form of energy may be used e.g. wind.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The photovoltaic power generation serves to reduce the consumption of non renewable fuel.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Hybrid systems are most often found on islands.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Pellworm island in Germany and Kythnos island in Greece are notable examples (both are combined with wind).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The Kythnos plant has reduced diesel consumption by 11.2%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In 2015, a case-study conducted in seven countries concluded that in all cases generating costs can be reduced by hybridising mini-grids and isolated grids.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] However, financing costs for such hybrids are crucial and largely depend on the ownership structure of the power plant.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] While cost reductions for state-owned utilities can be significant, the study also identified economic benefits to be insignificant or even negative for non-public utilities, such as independent power producers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] There has also been work showing that the PV penetration limit can be increased by deploying a distributed network of PV+CHP hybrid systems in the US.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] This theory was reconfirmed with numerical simulations using per second solar flux data to determine that the necessary battery backup to provide for such a hybrid system is possible with relatively small and inexpensive battery systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In addition, large PV+CHP systems are possible for institutional buildings, which again provide back up for intermittent PV and reduce CHP runtime.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Floating solar or floating photovoltaics (FPV), sometimes called floatovoltaics, are solar panels mounted on a structure that floats.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The structures that hold the panels usually consist of plastic buoys and cables.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] They are then placed on a body of water (e.g., Reservoirs, quarry lakes, irrigation canals or remediation and tailing ponds).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The systems can have advantages over photovoltaics (PV) on land.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Water surfaces may be less expensive than the cost of land, and there are fewer rules and regulations for structures built on bodies of water not used for recreation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Life cycle analysis indicates that foam-based FPV have some of the shortest energy payback times (1.3 years) and the lowest greenhouse gas emissions to energy ratio (11 kg CO2 eq/MWh) in crystalline silicon solar photovoltaic technologies reported.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] FPV can be used to generate electricity for any application as well as to make green hydrogen via electrolysis on the same water they are floating on.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Floating arrays can achieve higher efficiencies than PV panels on land because water cools the panels.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The panels can have a special coating to prevent rust or corrosion.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Floating SPV also provide shade, slow evaporation and inhibit the growth of algae.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The market for this renewable energy technology has grown rapidly since 2016.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The first 20 plants with capacities of a few dozen kWp were built between 2007 and 2013.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Installed power grew from 3 GW in 2020, to 13 GW in 2022, surpassing a prediction of 10 GW by 2025.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The World Bank estimated there are 6,600 large bodies of water suitable for floating solar, with a technical capacity of over 4,000 GW if 10% of their surfaces were covered with panels.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The US has more floating solar potential than any other country in the world.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Bodies of water suitable for floating solar are well-distributed throughout the US The southeast and southern US plains states generally have reservoirs with the largest capacities.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] DC grids are found in electric powered transport: railways trams and trolleybuses.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] A few pilot plants for such applications have been built, such as the tram depots in Hannover Leinhausen, using photovoltaic contributors and Geneva (Bachet de Pesay).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The 150 kWp Geneva site feeds 600 V DC directly into the tram/trolleybus electricity network whereas before it provided about 15% of the electricity at its opening in 1999.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] A stand-alone or off-grid system is not connected to the electrical grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Standalone systems vary widely in size and application from wristwatches or calculators to remote buildings or spacecraft.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] If the load is to be supplied independently of solar insolation, the generated power is stored and buffered with a battery.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In non-portable applications where weight is not an issue, such as in buildings, lead acid batteries are most commonly used for their low cost and tolerance for abuse.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] A charge controller may be incorporated in the system to avoid battery damage by excessive charging or discharging.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] It may also help to optimize production from the solar array using a maximum power point tracking technique (MPPT).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] However, in simple PV systems where the PV module voltage is matched to the battery voltage, the use of MPPT electronics is generally considered unnecessary, since the battery voltage is stable enough to provide near-maximum power collection from the PV module.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In small devices (e.g. calculators, parking meters) only direct current (DC) is consumed.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In larger systems (e.g. buildings, remote water pumps) AC is usually required.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] To convert the DC from the modules or batteries into AC, an inverter is used.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In agricultural settings, the array may be used to directly power DC pumps, without the need for an inverter.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In remote settings such as mountainous areas, islands, or other places where a power grid is unavailable, solar arrays can be used as the sole source of electricity, usually by charging a storage battery.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Stand-alone systems closely relate to microgeneration and distributed generation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] History of solar rooftop prices 2006–2013.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The cost of producing photovoltaic cells has dropped because of economies of scale in production and technological advances in manufacturing.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] For large-scale installations, prices below $1.00 per watt were common by 2012.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] A price decrease of 50% had been achieved in Europe from 2006 to 2011, and there was a potential to lower the generation cost by 50% by 2020.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Crystal silicon solar cells have largely been replaced by less expensive multicrystalline silicon solar cells, and thin film silicon solar cells have also been developed at lower costs of production.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Although they are reduced in energy conversion efficiency from single crystalline "siwafers", they are also much easier to produce at comparably lower costs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The table below shows the total (average) cost in US cents per kWh of electricity generated by a photovoltaic system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The row headings on the left show the total cost, per peak kilowatt (kWp), of a photovoltaic installation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Photovoltaic system costs have been declining and in Germany, for example, were reported to have fallen to USD 1389/kWp by the end of 2014.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The column headings across the top refer to the annual energy output in kWh expected from each installed kWp.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] This varies by geographic region because the average insolation depends on the average cloudiness and the thickness of atmosphere traversed by the sunlight.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] It also depends on the path of the sun relative to the panel and the horizon.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Panels are usually mounted at an angle based on latitude, and often they are adjusted seasonally to meet the changing solar declination.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Solar tracking can also be utilized to access even more perpendicular sunlight, thereby raising the total energy output.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The calculated values in the table reflect the total (average) cost in cents per kWh produced.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] They assume a 10% total capital cost (for instance 4% interest rate, 1% operating and maintenance cost, and depreciation of the capital outlay over 20 years).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Normally, photovoltaic modules have a 25-year warranty.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Generated kilowatt-hour per installed watt-peak, based on average insolation for Japan (1500 kWh/m2/year), United States (5.0 to 5.5 kWh/m2/day), and Germany (1000 to 1200 kWh/m2/year).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] A 2013 study by the Fraunhofer ISE concludes LCOE cost for a small PV system to be $0.16 (€0.12) rather than $0.22 per kilowatt-hour as shown in table (Germany).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Photovoltaic systems demonstrate a learning curve in terms of levelized cost of electricity (LCOE), reducing its cost per kWh by 32.6% for every doubling of capacity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Increasing use of photovoltaic systems and integration of photovoltaic power into existing structures and techniques of supply and distribution increases the need for general standards and definitions for photovoltaic components and systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The standards are compiled at the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) and apply to efficiency, durability and safety of cells, modules, simulation programs, plug connectors and cables, mounting systems, overall efficiency of inverters etc.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In the UK, PV installations are generally considered permitted development and do not require planning permission.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] If the property is listed or in a designated area (National Park, Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty, Site of Special Scientific Interest or Norfolk Broads) then planning permission is required.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] UK Solar PV installations are also subject to control under the Building Regulations 2010.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Buildings regulation approval is therefore necessary for both domestic and commercial solar PV rootop installations to ensure that they meet the required safety standards.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] This includes ensuring that the roof can support the weight of the solar panels, that the electrical connections are safe, and that there are no fire risks.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In the United States, article 690 of the National Electric Code provides general guidelines for the installation of photovoltaic systems; these may be superseded by local laws and regulations.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Often a permit is required necessitating plan submissions and structural calculations before work may begin.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Additionally, many locales require the work to be performed under the guidance of a licensed electrician.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The Authority Having Jurisdiction (AHJ) will review designs and issue permits, before construction can lawfully begin.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Electrical installation practices must comply with standards set forth within the National Electrical Code (NEC) and be inspected by the AHJ to ensure compliance with building code, electrical code, and fire safety code.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Jurisdictions may require that equipment has been tested, certified, listed, and labeled by at least one of the Nationally Recognized Testing Laboratories (NRTL).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Many localities require a permit to install a photovoltaic system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] A grid-tied system normally requires a licensed electrician to connect between the system and the grid-connected wiring of the building.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Installers who meet these qualifications are located in almost every state.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Several states prohibit homeowners' associations from restricting solar devices.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Those who do not connect to the grid can face up to a fine of 30 million euros (US$40 million).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Such measures were finally withdrawn by 2018, when new legislation was introduced banning any taxes on renewable energy self-consumption.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] With the increasing levels of rooftop photovoltaic systems, the energy flow becomes two-way.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] When there is more local generation than consumption, electricity is exported to the grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] However, electricity network traditionally is not designed to deal with the two-way energy transfer.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Therefore, some technical issues may occur.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] For example, in Queensland, Australia, there have been more than 30% of households with rooftop PV by the end of 2017.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The famous Californian 2020 duck curve appears very often for a lot of communities from 2015 onwards.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] An over-voltage issue may come out as the electricity flows back to the network.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] There are solutions to manage the over voltage issue, such as regulating PV inverter power factor, new voltage and energy control equipment at electricity distributor level, re-conductor the electricity wires, demand side management, etc.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] There are often limitations and costs related to these solutions.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Popular Mechanics reports that VOS results show that grid-tied utility customers are being grossly under-compensated in most of the US as the value of solar eclipses the net metering rate as well as two-tiered rates, which means "your neighbor's solar panels are secretly saving you money".
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Customers have different specific situations, e.g. different comfort/convenience needs, different electricity tariffs, or different usage patterns.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] An electricity tariff may have a few elements, such as daily access and metering charge, energy charge (based on kWh, MWh) or peak demand charge (e.g. a price for the highest 30min energy consumption in a month).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] PV is a promising option for reducing energy charge when electricity price is reasonably high and continuously increasing, such as in Australia and Germany.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] However, for sites with peak demand charge in place, PV may be less attractive if peak demands mostly occur in the late afternoon to early evening, for example residential communities.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Overall, energy investment is largely an economic decision and investment decisions are based on systematical evaluation of options in operational improvement, energy efficiency, onsite generation and energy storage.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] A grid-connected photovoltaic system, or grid-connected PV system is an electricity generating solar PV power system that is connected to the utility grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] A grid-connected PV system consists of solar panels, one or several inverters, a power conditioning unit and grid connection equipment.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] They range from small residential and commercial rooftop systems to large utility-scale solar power stations.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] When conditions are right, the grid-connected PV system supplies the excess power, beyond consumption by the connected load, to the utility grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Residential, grid-connected rooftop systems which have a capacity more than 10 kilowatts can meet the load of most consumers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] They can feed excess power to the grid where it is consumed by other users.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The feedback is done through a meter to monitor power transferred.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Photovoltaic wattage may be less than average consumption, in which case the consumer will continue to purchase grid energy, but a lesser amount than previously.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] If photovoltaic wattage substantially exceeds average consumption, the energy produced by the panels will be much in excess of the demand.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In this case, the excess power can yield revenue by selling it to the grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Depending on their agreement with their local grid energy company, the consumer only needs to pay the cost of electricity consumed less the value of electricity generated.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] This will be a negative number if more electricity is generated than consumed.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Additionally, in some cases, cash incentives are paid from the grid operator to the consumer.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Connection of the photovoltaic power system can be done only through an interconnection agreement between the consumer and the utility company.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The agreement details the various safety standards to be followed during the connection.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Electric power from photovoltaic panels must be converted to alternating current by a special power inverter if it is intended for delivery to a power grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The inverter sits between the solar array and the grid, and may be a large stand-alone unit or may be a collection of small inverters attached to individual solar panels as an AC module.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The inverter must monitor grid voltage, waveform, and frequency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The inverter must detect failure of the grid supply, and then, must not supply power to the grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] An inverter connected to a malfunctioning power line will automatically disconnect in accordance with safety rules, which vary by jurisdiction.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The location of the fault current plays a crucial part in deciding whether the protection mechanism of the inverter will kick in, especially for low and medium electricity supply network.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] A protection system must ensure proper operation for faults external to the inverter on the supply network.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] The special inverter must also be designed to synchronize its AC frequency with the grid, to ensure the correct integration of the inverter power flow into the grid according to the waveform.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Islanding is the condition in which a distributed generator continues to power a location even though power from the electric utility grid is no longer present.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] Islanding can be dangerous to utility workers, who may not realize that a circuit is still powered, even though there is no power from the electrical grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] For that reason, distributed generators must detect islanding and immediately stop producing power; this is referred to as anti-islanding.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In the case of a utility blackout in a grid-connected PV system, the solar panels will continue to deliver power as long as the sun is shining.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In this case, the supply line becomes an "island" with power surrounded by a "sea" of unpowered lines.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] For this reason, solar inverters that are designed to supply power to the grid are generally required to have automatic anti-islanding circuitry in them.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] In intentional islanding, the generator disconnects from the grid, and forces the distributed generator to power the local circuit.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaic-system-p02] This is often used as a power backup system for buildings that normally sell their power to the grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] A photovoltaic system employs solar modules, each comprising a number of solar cells, which generate electrical power.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] PV installations may be ground-mounted, rooftop-mounted, wall-mounted or floating.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The mount may be fixed or use a solar tracker to follow the sun across the sky.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic technology helps to mitigate climate change because it emits much less carbon dioxide than fossil fuels.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Other major constraints identified include competition for land use.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The use of PV as a main source requires energy storage systems or global distribution by high-voltage direct current power lines causing additional costs, and also has a number of other specific disadvantages such as variable power generation which have to be balanced.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Production and installation does cause some pollution and greenhouse gas emissions, though only a fraction of the emissions caused by fossil fuels.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic systems have long been used in specialized applications as stand-alone installations and grid-connected PV systems have been in use since the 1990s.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic modules were first mass-produced in 2000, when the German government funded a one hundred thousand roof program.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Decreasing costs has allowed PV to grow as an energy source.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This has been partially driven by massive Chinese government investment in developing solar production capacity since 2000, and achieving economies of scale.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Improvements in manufacturing technology and efficiency have also led to decreasing costs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Net metering and financial incentives, such as preferential feed-in tariffs for solar-generated electricity, have supported solar PV installations in many countries.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Panel prices dropped by a factor of 4 between 2004 and 2011.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Module prices dropped by about 90% over the 2010s.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In 2022, worldwide installed PV capacity increased to more than 1 terawatt (TW) covering nearly two percent of global electricity demand.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] After hydro and wind powers, PV is the third renewable energy source in terms of global capacity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In 2022, the International Energy Agency expected a growth by over 1 TW from 2022 to 2027.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In some instances, PV has offered the cheapest source of electrical power in regions with a high solar potential, with a bid for pricing as low as 0.015 US$/kWh in Qatar in 2023.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In 2023, the International Energy Agency stated in its World Energy Outlook that '[f]or projects with low cost financing that tap high quality resources, solar PV is now the cheapest source of electricity in history.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The term "photovoltaic" comes from the Greek φῶς (*phōs*) meaning "light", and from "volt", the unit of electromotive force, the volt, which in turn comes from the last name of the Italian physicist Alessandro Volta, inventor of the battery (electrochemical cell).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The term "photovoltaic" has been in use in English since 1849.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In 1839, the French scientist Edmond Becquerel first observed the photovoltaic effect when he noted an electric current was produced by a metallic solution exposed to solar radiation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In 1989, the German Ministry of Research and Technology initiated the first ever program to finance PV roofs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The program was led by Walter Sandtner in Bonn, Germany.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In 1994, Japan followed in their footsteps and conducted a similar program with 539 residential PV systems installed.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Since then, many countries have continued to produce and finance PV systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaics are best known as a method for generating electric power by using solar cells to convert energy from the sun into a flow of electrons by the photovoltaic effect.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Solar cells produce direct current electricity from sunlight which can be used to power equipment or to recharge batteries.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The first practical application of photovoltaics was to power orbiting satellites and other spacecraft, but today the majority of photovoltaic modules are used for grid-connected systems for power generation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In this case an inverter is required to convert the DC to AC.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] There is also a smaller market for stand alone systems for remote dwellings, boats, recreational vehicles, electric cars, roadside emergency telephones, remote sensing, and cathodic protection of pipelines.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic power generation employs solar modules composed of a number of solar cells containing a semiconductor material.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Copper solar cables connect modules (module cable), arrays (array cable), and sub-fields.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Because of the growing demand for renewable energy sources, the manufacturing of solar cells and photovoltaic arrays has advanced considerably in recent years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Cells require protection from the environment and are usually packaged tightly in solar modules.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic module power is measured under standard test conditions (STC) in "Wp" (watts peak).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The actual power output at a particular place may be less than or greater than this rated value, depending on geographical location, time of day, weather conditions, and other factors.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Solar photovoltaic array capacity factors are typically under 25% when not coupled with storage, which is lower than many other industrial sources of electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Solar-cell efficiency is the portion of energy in sunlight that is converted into electricity by a solar cell.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Efficiency, in combination with latitude and weather, determine the energy output of a solar system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] As of 2024, the record for solar cell efficiency was 47.6%, set in May 2022 by Fraunhofer ISE, with a III-V four-junction concentrating photovoltaic (CPV) cell.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The record in real-world conditions is held by NREL, which developed triple junction cells with a tested efficiency of 39.5%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Commercial solar modules may exceed 24% efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] As of 2025, the best reached 24.5%, typically lower than their cells in isolation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The most efficient mass-produced solar modules have power density values of 175 W/m2 (16.22 W/ft2).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In 2026 using triple III-V germanium cells and shingled matrix technology to interconnect cells, Fraunhofer achieved efficiency of 34.4%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] An important innovation was the use of direct cell-to-cell contact, eliminating traditional solder-coated copper ribbons and the resulting shading of active cell areas.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Several factors affect conversion efficiency, including its reflectance, thermodynamic efficiency, charge carrier separation efficiency, charge carrier collection efficiency and conduction efficiency values.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Because these parameters are difficult to directly measure, other parameters are measured instead, including quantum efficiency, open-circuit voltage (VOC) ratio, and § Fill factor.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Reflectance losses are accounted for by the quantum efficiency value, as they affect external quantum efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Recombination losses are accounted for by these factors.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Resistive losses are predominantly accounted for by the fill factor value, but also contribute to the others.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Depending on construction, photovoltaic modules can produce electricity from a range of frequencies of light, but usually cannot cover the entire solar radiation range (specifically, ultraviolet, visible, infrared and low or diffused light).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Hence, much of the incident sunlight energy is not processed by solar modules.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Sunlight can be split into wavelength bands (each a different color), each directed onto cells tuned to those ranges that can convert that band more efficiently.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Module performance is generally rated under standard test conditions (STC): irradiance of 1,000 W/m2, solar spectrum of AM 1.5 and module temperature at 25 °C.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The actual voltage and current output of the module changes as lighting, temperature and load conditions change, so there is never one specific voltage at which the module operates.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Performance varies depending on geographic location, time of day, the day of the year, amount of solar irradiance, direction and tilt of modules, cloud cover, shading, soiling, state of charge, and temperature.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Performance of a module or panel can be measured at different time intervals with a DC clamp meter or shunt and logged, graphed, or charted with a chart recorder or data logger.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] For optimum performance, a solar panel needs to be made of similar modules oriented in the same direction perpendicular to direct sunlight.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Bypass diodes are used to circumvent broken or shaded panels and optimize output.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] These bypass diodes are usually placed along groups of solar cells to create a continuous flow.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Electrical characteristics include nominal power (PMAX, measured in W), open-circuit voltage (VOC), short-circuit current (ISC, measured in amperes), maximum power voltage (VMPP), maximum power current (IMPP), peak power (watt-peak, Wp), and module efficiency (%).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Open-circuit voltage or VOC is the maximum voltage the module can produce when not connected to an electrical circuit or system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] VOC can be measured with a voltmeter directly on an illuminated module's terminals or on its disconnected cable.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The peak power rating, Wp, is the maximum output under standard test conditions (not the maximum possible output).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Typical modules, which could measure approximately 1 by 2 metres (3 ft × 7 ft), will be rated from as low as 75 W to as high as 600 W, depending on their efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] At the time of testing, the test modules are binned according to their test results, and a typical manufacturer might rate their modules in 5 W increments, and either rate them at +/- 3%, +/-5%, +3/-0% or +5/-0%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The performance of a photovoltaic (PV) module depends on the environmental conditions, mainly on the global incident irradiance G in the plane of the module.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] However, the temperature T of the p–n junction also influences the main electrical parameters: the short circuit current ISC, the open circuit voltage VOC and the maximum power Pmax.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In general, it is known that VOC shows a significant inverse correlation with T, while for ISC this correlation is direct, but weaker, so that this increase does not compensate for the decrease in VOC.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] As a consequence, Pmax decreases when T increases.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Temperature sensitivity is usually described by temperature coefficients, each of which expresses the derivative of the parameter to which it refers with respect to the junction temperature.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Techniques for estimating these coefficients from experimental data can be found in the literature.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The ability of solar modules to withstand damage by rain, hail, heavy snow load, and cycles of heat and cold varies by manufacturer, although most solar panels on the U.S. market are UL listed, meaning they have gone through testing to withstand hail.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Potential-induced degradation (also called PID) is a potential-induced performance degradation in crystalline photovoltaic modules, caused by so-called stray currents.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This effect may cause power loss of up to 30%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The largest challenge for photovoltaic technology is the purchase price per watt of electricity produced.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Advancements in photovoltaic technologies have brought about the process of "doping" the silicon substrate to lower the activation energy thereby making the panel more efficient in converting photons to retrievable electrons.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Chemicals such as boron (p-type) are applied into the semiconductor crystal in order to create donor and acceptor energy levels substantially closer to the valence and conductor bands.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In doing so, the addition of boron impurity allows the activation energy to decrease twenty-fold from 1.12 eV to 0.05 eV.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Since the potential difference (EB) is so low, the boron is able to thermally ionize at room temperatures.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This allows for free energy carriers in the conduction and valence bands thereby allowing greater conversion of photons to electrons.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The power output of a photovoltaic (PV) device decreases over time.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This decrease is due to its exposure to solar radiation as well as other external conditions.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The degradation index, which is defined as the annual percentage of output power loss, is a key factor in determining the long-term production of a photovoltaic plant.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] To estimate this degradation, the percentage of decrease associated with each of the electrical parameters.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The individual degradation of a photovoltaic module can significantly influence the performance of a complete string.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Furthermore, not all modules in the same installation decrease their performance at exactly the same rate.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Given a set of modules exposed to long-term outdoor conditions, the individual degradation of the main electrical parameters and the increase in their dispersion must be considered.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] As each module tends to degrade differently, the behavior of the modules will be increasingly different over time, negatively affecting the overall performance of the plant.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] There are several studies dealing with the power degradation analysis of modules based on different photovoltaic technologies available in the literature.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] According to a recent study, the degradation of crystalline silicon modules is very regular, oscillating between 0.8% and 1.0% per year.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Strong seasonal variations are also observed in such thin-film technologies because the influence of the solar spectrum is much greater.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] For example, for modules of amorphous silicon, micromorphic silicon or cadmium telluride, we are talking about annual degradation rates for the first years of between 3% and 4%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] However, other technologies, such as CIGS, show much lower degradation rates, even in those early years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Overall the manufacturing process of creating solar photovoltaics is simple in that it does not require the culmination of many complex or moving parts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Because of the solid-state nature of PV systems, they often have relatively long lifetimes, anywhere from 10 to 30 years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] To increase the electrical output of a PV system, the manufacturer must simply add more photovoltaic components.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Because of this, economies of scale are important for manufacturers as costs decrease with increasing output.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] While there are many types of PV systems known to be effective, crystalline silicon PV accounted for around 90% of the worldwide production of PV in 2013.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Manufacturing silicon PV systems has several steps.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] First, polysilicon is processed from mined quartz until it is very pure (semi-conductor grade).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This is melted down with small amounts of boron, a group III element, to make a p-type semiconductor rich in electron holes.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Typically using a seed crystal, an ingot of this solution is grown from the liquid polycrystalline.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Wafers of this semiconductor material are cut from the bulk material with wire saws, and then go through surface etching before being cleaned.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Next, the wafers are placed into a phosphorus vapor deposition furnace which lays a very thin layer of phosphorus, a group V element, which creates an n-type semiconducting surface.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] To reduce energy losses, an anti-reflective coating is added to the surface, along with electrical contacts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] After finishing the cell, cells are connected via electrical circuit according to the specific application and prepared for shipping and installation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Data required to investigate their impact are sometimes affected by a rather large amount of uncertainty.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The values of human labor and water consumption, for example, are not precisely assessed due to the lack of systematic and accurate analyses in the scientific literature.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] One difficulty in determining effects due to PV is to determine if the wastes are released to the air, water, or soil during the manufacturing phase.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Life-cycle assessments, which look at all different environment effects ranging from global warming potential, pollution, water depletion and others, are unavailable for PV.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Thus, estimates of the environmental impact of PV have focused on carbon dioxide equivalents per kWh or energy pay-back time (EPBT).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The EPBT describes the timespan a PV system needs to operate in order to generate the same amount of energy that was used for its manufacture.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Another study includes transport energy costs in the EPBT.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The EPBT has also been defined completely differently as "the time needed to compensate for the total renewable- and non-renewable primary energy required during the life cycle of a PV system" in another study, which also included installation costs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This energy amortization, given in years, is also referred to as *break-even* energy payback time.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The lower the EPBT, the lower the environmental cost of solar power.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The EPBT depends vastly on the location where the PV system is installed (e.g. the amount of sunlight available and the efficiency of the electrical grid) and on the type of system, namely the system's components.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] A 2015 review of EPBT estimates of first and second-generation PV suggested that there was greater variation in embedded energy than in efficiency of the cells implying that it was mainly the embedded energy that needs to reduce to have a greater reduction in EPBT.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In general, the most important component of solar panels, which accounts for much of the energy use and greenhouse gas emissions, is the refining of the polysilicon.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] As to how much percentage of the EPBT this silicon depends on the type of system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The EPBT relates closely to the concepts of net energy gain (NEG) and energy returned on energy invested (EROI).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] They are both used in energy economics and refer to the difference between the energy expended to harvest an energy source and the amount of energy gained from that harvest.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The NEG and EROI also take the operating lifetime of a PV system into account and a working life of 25 to 30 years is typically assumed.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] From these metrics, the Energy payback Time can be derived by calculation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] PV systems using crystalline silicon, by far the majority of the systems in practical use, have such a high EPBT because silicon is produced by the reduction of high-grade quartz sand in electric furnaces.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This coke-fired smelting process occurs at high temperatures of more than 1000 °C and is very energy intensive, using about 11 kilowatt-hours (kWh) per produced kilogram of silicon.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The energy requirements of this process makes the energy cost per unit of silicon produced relatively inelastic, which means that the production process itself will not become more efficient in the future.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Nonetheless, the energy payback time has shortened significantly over the last years, as crystalline silicon cells became ever more efficient in converting sunlight, while the thickness of the wafer material was constantly reduced and therefore required less silicon for its manufacture.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Within the last ten years, the amount of silicon used for solar cells declined from 16 to 6 grams per watt-peak.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In the same period, the thickness of a c-Si wafer was reduced from 300 μm, or microns, to about 160–190 μm.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The sawing techniques that slice crystalline silicon ingots into wafers have also improved by reducing the kerf loss and making it easier to recycle the silicon sawdust.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Crystalline silicon modules are the most extensively studied PV type in terms of LCA since they are the most commonly used.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Mono-crystalline silicon photovoltaic systems (mono-si) have an average efficiency of 14.0%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The cells tend to follow a structure of front electrode, anti-reflection film, n-layer, p-layer, and back electrode, with the sun hitting the front electrode.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The cradle to gate of CO2-eq/kWh ranges from 37.3 to 72.2 grams when installed in Southern Europe.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Techniques to produce multi-crystalline silicon (multi-si) photovoltaic cells are simpler and cheaper than mono-si, however tend to make less efficient cells, an average of 13.2%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The cradle to gate of CO2-eq/kWh ranges from 28.5 to 69 grams when installed in Southern Europe.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Outside of Europe, where net grid efficiencies are lower, it would take longer.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This 'energy payback time' can be seen as the portion of time during the useful lifetime of the module in which the energy production is polluting.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] At best, this means that a 30-year old panel has produced clean energy for 97% of its lifetime, or that the silicon in the modules in a solar panel produce 97% less greenhouse gas emissions than a coal-fired plant for the same amount of energy (assuming and ignoring many things).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Some studies have looked beyond EPBT and GWP to other environmental effects.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In one such study, conventional energy mix in Greece was compared to multi-si PV and found a 95% overall reduction in effects including carcinogens, eco-toxicity, acidification, eutrophication, and eleven others.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Cadmium telluride (CdTe) is one of the fastest-growing thin film based solar cells which are collectively known as second-generation devices.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This new thin-film device also shares similar performance restrictions (Shockley-Queisser efficiency limit) as conventional Si devices but promises to lower the cost of each device by both reducing material and energy consumption during manufacturing.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The global market share of CdTe was 4.7% in 2008.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This technology's highest power conversion efficiency is 21%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The cell structure includes glass substrate (around 2 mm), transparent conductor layer, CdS buffer layer (50–150 nm), CdTe absorber and a metal contact layer.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] CdTe PV systems require less energy input in their production than other commercial PV systems per unit electricity production.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The average CO2-eq/kWh is around 18 grams (cradle to gate).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] CdTe has the fastest EPBT of all commercial PV technologies, which varies between 0.3 and 1.2 years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Third-generation PVs are designed to combine the advantages of both the first and second generation devices and they do not have Shockley-Queisser limit, a theoretical limit for first and second generation PV cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The thickness of a third generation device is less than 1 μm.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Two new promising thin film technologies are copper zinc tin sulfide (Cu2ZnSnS4 or CZTS), zinc phosphide (Zn3P2) and single-walled carbon nano-tubes (SWCNT).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] These thin films are currently only produced in the lab but may be commercialized in the future.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The manufacturing of CZTS and (Zn3P2) processes are expected to be similar to those of current thin film technologies of CIGS and CdTe, respectively.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] While CZTS and Zn3P2 offer good promise for these reasons, the specific environmental implications of their commercial production are not yet known.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Global warming potential of CZTS and Zn3P2 were found 38 and 30 grams CO2-eq/kWh while their corresponding EPBT were found 1.85 and 0.78 years, respectively.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Overall, CdTe and Zn3P2 have similar environmental effects but can slightly outperform CIGS and CZTS.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] A study on environmental impacts of SWCNT PVs by Celik et al., including an existing 1% efficient device and a theoretical 28% efficient device, found that, compared to monocrystalline Si, the environmental impacts from 1% SWCNT was ~18 times higher due mainly to the short lifetime of three years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] There have been major changes in the underlying costs, industry structure and market prices of solar photovoltaics technology, over the years, and gaining a coherent picture of the shifts occurring across the industry value chain globally is a challenge.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Further complexities result from the many different policy support initiatives that have been put in place to facilitate photovoltaics commercialisation in various countries.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Renewable energy technologies have generally gotten cheaper since their invention.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Renewable energy systems have become cheaper to build than fossil fuel power plants across much of the world, thanks to advances in wind and solar energy technology, in particular.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] There is no silver bullet in electricity or energy demand and bill management, because customers (sites) have different specific situations, e.g. different comfort/convenience needs, different electricity tariffs, or different usage patterns.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Electricity tariff may have a few elements, such as daily access and metering charge, energy charge (based on kWh, MWh) or peak demand charge (e.g. a price for the highest 30min energy consumption in a month).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] PV is a promising option for reducing energy charges when electricity prices are reasonably high and continuously increasing, such as in Australia and Germany.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] However, for sites with peak demand charge in place, PV may be less attractive if peak demands mostly occur in the late afternoon to early evening, for example in residential communities.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Overall, energy investment is largely an economic decision and it is better to make investment decisions based on systematic evaluation of options in operational improvement, energy efficiency, onsite generation and energy storage.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In 1977 crystalline silicon solar cell prices were at $76.67/W.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Manufacturers were able to maintain a positive operating margin despite a 50% drop in income due to innovation and reductions in costs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In late 2011, factory-gate prices for crystalline-silicon photovoltaic modules suddenly dropped below the $1.00/W mark, taking many in the industry by surprise, and has caused a number of solar manufacturing companies to go bankrupt throughout the world.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The $1.00/W cost is often regarded in the PV industry as marking the achievement of grid parity for PV, but most experts do not believe this price point is sustainable.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Technological advancements, manufacturing process improvements, and industry re-structuring, may mean that further price reductions are possible.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The average retail price of solar cells as monitored by the Solarbuzz group fell from $3.50/watt to $2.43/watt over the course of 2011.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In 2013 wholesale prices had fallen to $0.74/W.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This has been cited as evidence supporting 'Swanson's law', an observation similar to the famous Moore's Law, which claims that solar cell prices fall 20% for every doubling of industry capacity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The Fraunhofer Institute defines the 'learning rate' as the drop in prices as the cumulative production doubles, some 25% between 1980 and 2010.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Although the prices for modules have dropped quickly, current inverter prices have dropped at a much lower rate, and in 2019 constitute over 61% of the cost per kWp, from a quarter in the early 2000s.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Note that the prices mentioned above are for bare modules, another way of looking at module prices is to include installation costs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In the US, according to the Solar Energy Industries Association, the price of installed rooftop PV modules for homeowners fell from $9.00/W in 2006 to $5.46/W in 2011.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Including the prices paid by industrial installations, the national installed price drops to $3.45/W.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This is markedly higher than elsewhere in the world, in Germany homeowner rooftop installations averaged at $2.24/W.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The cost differences are thought to be primarily based on the higher regulatory burden and lack of a national solar policy in the US.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] By the end of 2012 Chinese manufacturers had production costs of $0.50/W in the cheapest modules.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In some markets distributors of these modules can earn a considerable margin, buying at factory-gate price and selling at the highest price the market can support ('value-based pricing').
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In California PV reached grid parity in 2011, which is usually defined as PV production costs at or below retail electricity prices (though often still above the power station prices for coal or gas-fired generation without their distribution and other costs).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Grid parity had been reached in 19 markets in 2014.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] By 2024, massive increases of production of solar panels in China had caused module prices to drop to as low as $0.11/W, an over 90 percent reduction from 2011 prices.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The levelised cost of electricity (LCOE) is the cost per kWh based on the costs distributed over the project lifetime, and is thought to be a better metric for calculating viability than price per wattage.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] LCOEs vary dramatically depending on the location.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The LCOE can be considered the minimum price customers will have to pay the utility company in order for it to break even on the investment in a new power station.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Grid parity is roughly achieved when the LCOE falls to a similar price as conventional local grid prices, although in actuality the calculations are not directly comparable.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Large industrial PV installations had reached grid parity in California in 2011.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Grid parity for rooftop systems was still believed to be much farther away at this time.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Many LCOE calculations are not thought to be accurate, and a large amount of assumptions are required.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Module prices may drop further, and the LCOE for solar may correspondingly drop in the future.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] These costs are not factored into LCOE calculations, nor are special subsidies or premiums that may make buying solar power more attractive.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The unreliability and temporal variation in generation of solar and wind power is a major problem.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Too much of these volatile power sources can cause instability of the entire grid.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] As of 2017 power-purchase agreement prices for solar farms below $0.05/kWh are common in the United States, and the lowest bids in some Persian Gulf countries were about $0.03/kWh.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The goal of the United States Department of Energy is to achieve a levelised cost of energy for solar PV of $0.03/kWh for utility companies.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Financial incentives for photovoltaics, such as feed-in tariffs (FITs), were often offered to electricity consumers to install and operate solar-electric generating systems, and in some countries such subsidies are the only way photovoltaics can remain economically profitable.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] PV FITs were crucial for early growth of photovoltaics.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Germany and Spain were the most important countries offering subsidies for PV, and the policies of these countries drove demand.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Some US solar cell manufacturing companies have repeatedly complained that the dropping prices of PV module costs have been achieved due to subsidies by the government of China, and the dumping of these products below fair market prices.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] US manufacturers generally recommend high tariffs on foreign supplies to allow them remain profitable.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In response to these concerns, the Obama administration began to levy tariffs on US consumers of these products in 2012 to raise prices for domestic manufacturers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The USA, however, also subsidies the industry.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Some environmentalists have promoted the idea that government incentives should be used in order to expand the PV manufacturing industry to reduce costs of PV-generated electricity much more rapidly to a level where it is able to compete with fossil fuels in a free market.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This is based on the theory that when the manufacturing capacity doubles, economies of scale will cause the prices of the solar products to halve.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In many countries access to capital is lacking to develop PV projects.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] To solve this problem, securitization is sometimes used to accelerate development of solar photovoltaic projects.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Photovoltaic power is also generated during a time of day that is close to peak demand (precedes it) in electricity systems with high use of air conditioning.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Since large-scale PV operation requires back-up in the form of spinning reserves, its marginal cost of generation in the middle of the day is typically lowest, but not zero, when PV is generating electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This can be seen in Figure 1 of this paper:.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] For residential properties with private PV facilities networked to the grid, the owner may be able earn extra money when the time of generation is included, as electricity is worth more during the day than at night.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] One journalist theorised in 2012 that if the energy bills of Americans were forced upwards by imposing an extra tax of $50/ton on carbon dioxide emissions from coal-fired power, this could have allowed solar PV to appear more cost-competitive to consumers in most locations.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Solar and wind power are scaling up faster than previous sources of electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Declining costs, modular design, and improved battery storage help the transition to renewable energy, especially for solar.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Solar photovoltaics formed the largest body of research among the seven sustainable energy types examined in a global bibliometric study, with the annual scientific output growing from 9,094 publications in 2011 to 14,447 publications in 2019.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Likewise, the application of solar photovoltaics is growing rapidly and the worldwide installed capacity reached one terawatt in April 2022.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The total power output of the world's PV capacity in a calendar year is now beyond 500 TWh of electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] This represents 2% of worldwide electricity demand.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] More than 100 countries, such as Brazil and India, use solar PV.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] China is followed by the United States and Japan, while installations in Germany, once the world's largest producer, have been slowing down.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Honduras generated the highest percentage of its energy from solar in 2019, 14.8%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] As of 2019, Vietnam has the highest installed capacity in Southeast Asia, about 4.5 GW.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The annualized installation rate of about 90 W per capita per annum places Vietnam among world leaders.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Generous Feed-in tariff (FIT) and government supporting policies such as tax exemptions were the key to enable Vietnam's solar PV boom.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Underlying drivers include the government's desire to enhance energy self-sufficiency and the public's demand for local environmental quality.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] A key barrier is limited transmission grid capacity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] China has the world's largest solar power capacity, with 1048 GW of installed capacity in 2024 compared with about 339 GW in the European Union, according to International Energy Agency data.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Other countries with the world's largest solar power capacities include the United States, Japan and Germany.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] In 2017, it was thought probable that by 2030 global PV installed capacities could be between 3,000 and 10,000 GW.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Greenpeace in 2010 claimed that 1,845 GW of PV systems worldwide could be generating approximately 2,646 TWh/year of electricity by 2030, and by 2050 over 20% of all electricity could be provided by PV.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] There are many practical applications for the use of solar panels or photovoltaics covering every technological domain under the sun.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] From the fields of the agricultural industry as a power source for irrigation to its usage in remote health care facilities to refrigerate medical supplies.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Other applications include power generation at various scales and attempts to integrate them into homes and public infrastructure.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] PV modules are used in photovoltaic systems and include a large variety of electrical devices.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] A photovoltaic system, or solar PV system is a power system designed to supply usable solar power by means of photovoltaics.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] It consists of an arrangement of several components, including solar panels to absorb and directly convert sunlight into electricity, a solar inverter to change the electric current from DC to AC, as well as mounting, cabling and other electrical accessories.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] PV systems range from small, roof-top mounted or building-integrated systems with capacities from a few to several tens of kilowatts, to large utility-scale power stations of hundreds of megawatts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Nowadays, most PV systems are grid-connected, while stand-alone systems only account for a small portion of the market.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Photosensors are sensors of light or other electromagnetic radiation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] A photo detector has a p–n junction that converts light photons into current.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] The absorbed photons make electron–hole pairs in the depletion region.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Photodiodes and photo transistors are a few examples of photo detectors.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p01] Solar cells convert some of the light energy absorbed into electrical energy.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Crystalline silicon photovoltaics are only one type of PV, and while they represent the majority of solar cells produced currently there are many new and promising technologies that have the potential to be scaled up to meet future energy needs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] As of 2018, crystalline silicon cell technology serves as the basis for several PV module types, including monocrystalline, multicrystalline, mono PERC, and bifacial.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Another newer technology, thin-film PV, are manufactured by depositing semiconducting layers of perovskite, a mineral with semiconductor properties, on a substrate in vacuum.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The substrate is often glass or stainless-steel, and these semiconducting layers are made of many types of materials including cadmium telluride (CdTe), copper indium diselenide (CIS), copper indium gallium diselenide (CIGS), and amorphous silicon (a-Si).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] After being deposited onto the substrate the semiconducting layers are separated and connected by electrical circuit by laser scribing.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Perovskite solar cells are a very efficient solar energy converter and have excellent optoelectronic properties for photovoltaic purposes, but their upscaling from lab-sized cells to large-area modules is still under research.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Thin-film photovoltaic materials may possibly become attractive in the future, because of the reduced materials requirements and cost to manufacture modules consisting of thin-films as compared to silicon-based wafers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] In 2019 university labs at Oxford, Stanford and elsewhere reported perovskite solar cells with efficiencies of 20-25%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Copper indium gallium selenide (CIGS) is a thin film solar cell based on the copper indium diselenide (CIS) family of chalcopyrite semiconductors.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] CIS and CIGS are often used interchangeably within the CIS/CIGS community.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The cell structure includes soda lime glass as the substrate, Mo layer as the back contact, CIS/CIGS as the absorber layer, cadmium sulfide (CdS) or Zn (S,OH)x as the buffer layer, and ZnO:Al as the front contact.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] CIGS is approximately 1/100 the thickness of conventional silicon solar cell technologies.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Materials necessary for assembly are readily available, and are less costly per watt of solar cell.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] CIGS based solar devices resist performance degradation over time and are highly stable in the field.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Reported global warming potential impacts of CIGS ranges 20.5–58.8 grams CO2-eq/kWh of electricity generated for different solar irradiation (1,700 to 2,200 kWh/m2/y) and power conversion efficiency (7.8 – 9.12%).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] EPBT ranges from 0.2 to 1.4 years, while harmonized value of EPBT was found 1.393 years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Toxicity is an issue within the buffer layer of CIGS modules because it contains cadmium and gallium.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] CIS modules do not contain any heavy metals.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] A perovskite solar cell (PSC) is a type of solar cell that includes a perovskite-structured compound, most commonly a hybrid organic–inorganic lead or tin halide-based material as the light-harvesting active layer.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Perovskite materials, such as methylammonium lead halides the all-inorganic cesium lead halide, are cheap to produce and simple to manufacture.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Solar-cell efficiencies of laboratory-scale devices using these materials have increased from 3.8% in 2009 to 27% in 2025 in single-junction architectures, and, in silicon-based tandem cells, to 34.85%, exceeding the maximum efficiency achieved in single-junction silicon solar cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Perovskite solar cells have therefore been the fastest-advancing solar technology as of 2016.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] With the potential of achieving even higher efficiencies and very low production costs, perovskite solar cells have become commercially attractive.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Core problems and research subjects include their long-term stability, high sensitivity to moisture, and toxicity if lead is used.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Managing toxic lead in PSCs is essential, as exposure presents significant health risks, including neurological disorders.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Because PSCs are an emerging technology, lead toxicity remains a major hurdle to widespread adoption and commercialization.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Dye-sensitized solar cells (DSCs) are a novel thin film solar cell.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] These solar cells operate under ambient light better than other photovoltaic technologies.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] They work with light being absorbed in a sensitizing dye between two charge transport materials.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Dye surrounds TiO2 nanoparticles which are in a sintered network.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] TiO2 acts as conduction band in an n-type semiconductor; the scaffold for adorned dye molecules and transports elections during excitation.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] For TiO2 DSC technology, sample preparation at high temperatures is very effective because higher temperatures produce more suitable textural properties.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Another example of DSCs is the copper complex with Cu (II/I) as a redox shuttle with TMBY (4,4',6,6'-tetramethyl-2,2'bipyridine).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] DSCs show great performance with artificial and indoor light.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] From a range of 200 lux to 2,000 lux, these cells operate at conditions of a maximum efficiency of 29.7%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] However, there have been issues with DSCs, many of which come from the liquid electrolyte.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The solvent is hazardous, and will permeate most plastics.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Because it is liquid, it is unstable to temperature variation, leading to freezing in cold temperatures and expansion in warm temperatures causing failure.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Another disadvantage is that the solar cell is not ideal for large scale application because of its low efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Some of the benefits for DSC is that it can be used in a variety of light levels (including cloudy conditions), it has a low production cost, and it does not degrade under sunlight, giving it a longer lifetime then other types of thin film solar cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Other possible future PV technologies include organic, dye-sensitized and quantum-dot photovoltaics.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Organic photovoltaics (OPVs) fall into the thin-film category of manufacturing, and typically operate around the 12% efficiency range which is lower than the 12–21% typically seen by silicon-based PVs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Because organic photovoltaics require very high purity and are relatively reactive they must be encapsulated which vastly increases the cost of manufacturing and means that they are not feasible for large scale-up.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Dye-sensitized PVs are similar in efficiency to OPVs but are significantly easier to manufacture.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] However, these dye-sensitized photovoltaics present storage problems because the liquid electrolyte is toxic and can potentially permeate the plastics used in the cell.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Quantum dot solar cells are solution-processed, meaning they are potentially scalable, but currently they peak at 12% efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Organic and polymer photovoltaic (OPV) are a relatively new area of research.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The tradition OPV cell structure layers consist of a semi-transparent electrode, electron blocking layer, tunnel junction, holes blocking layer, electrode, with the sun hitting the transparent electrode.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] OPV replaces silver with carbon as an electrode material lowering manufacturing cost and making them more environmentally friendly.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] OPV are flexible, low weight, and work well with roll-to roll manufacturing for mass production.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] OPV uses "only abundant elements coupled to an extremely low embodied energy through very low processing temperatures using only ambient processing conditions on simple printing equipment enabling energy pay-back times".
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Current efficiencies range 1–6.5%, however theoretical analyses show promise beyond 10% efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Many different configurations of OPV exist using different materials for each layer.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] OPV technology rivals existing PV technologies in terms of EPBT even if they currently present a shorter operational lifetime.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] A 2013 study analyzed 12 different configurations all with 2% efficiency, the EPBT ranged from 0.29 to 0.52 years for 1 m2 of PV.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The average CO2-eq/kWh for OPV is 54.922 grams.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Thermophotovoltaic (TPV) energy conversion is a direct conversion process from heat to electricity via photons.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] A basic thermophotovoltaic system consists of a hot object emitting thermal radiation and a photovoltaic cell similar to a solar cell but tuned to the spectrum being emitted from the hot object.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] As TPV systems generally work at lower temperatures than solar cells, their efficiencies tend to be low.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Offsetting this through the use of multi-junction cells based on non-silicon materials is common, but generally very expensive.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] This currently limits TPV to niche roles like spacecraft power and waste heat collection from larger systems like steam turbines.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Photovoltaic-Thermoelectric Generator (PV-TEG) hybrid system is a type of hybrid PV cell that pairs a photovoltaic (PV) cell with a thermoelectric generator (TEG).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] TEGs rely on the Seebeck effect, a phenomenon that occurs when a junction of two conducting materials experience a temperature difference thereby, inducing an electromotive force.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The resulting voltage is directly proportional to the temperature difference.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] During the process of converting light into electricity, heat dissipates, making PV cells less efficient at high temperatures and reducing their lifespan.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] By integrating a TEG into the system, heat is facilitated away from the PV cell and converts it into electricity, thereby improving its efficiency and longevity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The thermoelectric figure of merit ZT, determines the efficiency of converting heat into electricity as well as the ability to cool.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Optimizing parameters such as electrical conductivity (σ), Seebeck coefficient (S), thermal conductivity (κ) are of interest to maximize efficiencies.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Common thermoelectric materials typically have a ZT value of about 1, corresponding to an efficiency of approximately 10% or less.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] While typical TEGs have a low conversion efficiency, ongoing research in thermoelectric materials such as BiTe (ZT = 2.4) , SnSe (ZT = 2.6), and half-Heusler compounds (ZT = 1.6) have led to improvement in efficiency over the years.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Theoretical predictions indicate greater potential for optimization, with estimated values of 14 for BiTe, 2.6 for SnSe, and 2.2 for half-Heusler.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] A number of solar modules may also be mounted vertically above each other in a tower, if the zenith distance of the Sun is greater than zero, and the tower can be turned horizontally as a whole and each module additionally around a horizontal axis.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] In such a tower the modules can follow the Sun exactly.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Such a device may be described as a ladder mounted on a turnable disk.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Each step of that ladder is the middle axis of a rectangular solar panel.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] In case the zenith distance of the Sun reaches zero, the "ladder" may be rotated to the north or the south to avoid a solar module producing a shadow on a lower one.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Instead of an exactly vertical tower one can choose a tower with an axis directed to the polar star, meaning that it is parallel to the rotation axis of the Earth.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] In this case the angle between the axis and the Sun is always larger than 66 degrees.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] During a day it is only necessary to turn the panels around this axis to follow the Sun.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Installations may be ground-mounted (and sometimes integrated with farming and grazing) or built into the roof or walls of a building (building-integrated photovoltaics).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Where land may be limited, PV can be deployed as floating solar.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] In 2008 the Far Niente Winery pioneered the world's first "floatovoltaic" system by installing 994 photovoltaic solar panels onto 130 pontoons and floating them on the winery's irrigation pond.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] A benefit of the set up is that the panels are kept at a lower temperature than they would be on land, leading to a higher efficiency of solar energy conversion.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The floating panels also reduce the amount of water lost through evaporation and inhibit the growth of algae.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Concentrator photovoltaics is a technology that contrary to conventional flat-plate PV systems uses lenses and curved mirrors to focus sunlight onto small, but highly efficient, multi-junction solar cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] These systems sometimes use solar trackers and a cooling system to increase their efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] In 2019, the world record for solar cell efficiency at 47.1% was achieved by using multi-junction concentrator solar cells, developed at National Renewable Energy Laboratory, Colorado, US.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The highest efficiencies achieved without concentration include a material by Sharp Corporation at 35.8% using a proprietary triple-junction manufacturing technology in 2009, and Boeing Spectrolab (40.7% also using a triple-layer design).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] There is an ongoing effort to increase the conversion efficiency of PV cells and modules, primarily for competitive advantage.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] In order to increase the efficiency of solar cells, it is important to choose a semiconductor material with an appropriate band gap that matches the solar spectrum.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] This will enhance the electrical and optical properties.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Improving the method of charge collection is also useful for increasing the efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] There are several groups of materials that are being developed.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Ultrahigh-efficiency devices (η>30%) are made by using GaAs and GaInP2 semiconductors with multijunction tandem cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] High-quality, single-crystal silicon materials are used to achieve high-efficiency, low cost cells (η>20%).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Recent developments in organic photovoltaic cells (OPVs) have made significant advancements in power conversion efficiency from 3% to over 15% since their introduction in the 1980s.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] To date, the highest reported power conversion efficiency ranges 6.7–8.94% for small molecule, 8.4–10.6% for polymer OPVs, and 7–21% for perovskite OPVs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] OPVs are expected to play a major role in the PV market.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Recent improvements have increased the efficiency and lowered cost, while remaining environmentally-benign and renewable.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Several companies have begun embedding power optimizers into PV modules called smart modules.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] These modules perform maximum power point tracking (MPPT) for each module individually, measure performance data for monitoring, and provide additional safety features.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Such modules can also compensate for shading effects, wherein a shadow falling across a section of a module causes the electrical output of one or more strings of cells in the module to decrease.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] One of the major causes for the decreased performance of cells is overheating.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The efficiency of a solar cell declines by about 0.5% for every 1 degree Celsius increase in temperature.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] This means that a 100 degree increase in surface temperature could decrease the efficiency of a solar cell by about half.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Self-cooling solar cells are one solution to this problem.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Rather than using energy to cool the surface, pyramid and cone shapes can be formed from silica, and attached to the surface of a solar panel.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Doing so allows visible light to reach the solar cells, but reflects infrared rays (which carry heat).
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The 122 PW of sunlight reaching the Earth's surface is plentiful—almost 10,000 times more than the 13 TW equivalent of average power consumed in 2005 by humans.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] This abundance leads to the suggestion that it will not be long before solar energy will become the world's primary energy source.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Additionally, solar radiation has the highest power density (global mean of 170 W/m2) among renewable energies.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Solar power is pollution-free during use, which enables it to cut down on pollution when it is substituted for other energy sources.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] For example, MIT estimated that 52,000 people per year die prematurely in the U.S. from coal-fired power plant pollution and all but one of these deaths could be prevented from using PV to replace coal.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Production end-wastes and emissions are manageable using existing pollution controls.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] End-of-use recycling technologies are under development and policies are being produced that encourage recycling from producers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Solar panels are usually guaranteed for 25 years (but inverters tend to fail sooner), with little maintenance or intervention after their initial set-up, so after the initial capital cost of building any solar power plant, operating costs are extremely low compared to existing power technologies.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] One approach to improving PV environmental performance is with circular PV modules that are designed to be easily disassembled.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Rooftop solar can be used locally, thus reducing transmission/distribution losses.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Compared to fossil and nuclear energy sources, very little research money has been invested in the development of solar cells, so there is considerable room for improvement.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Nevertheless, experimental high efficiency solar cells already have efficiencies of over 40% in case of concentrating photovoltaic cells and efficiencies are rapidly rising while mass-production costs are rapidly falling.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] In some states of the United States, much of the investment in a home-mounted system may be lost if the homeowner moves and the buyer puts less value on the system than the seller.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] The city of Berkeley developed an innovative financing method to remove this limitation, by adding a tax assessment that is transferred with the home to pay for the solar panels.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] Now known as PACE, Property Assessed Clean Energy, 30 U.S. states have duplicated this solution.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] For behind-the-meter rooftop photovoltaic systems, the energy flow becomes two-way.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] When there is more local generation than consumption, electricity is exported to the grid, allowing for net metering.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] However, electricity networks traditionally are not designed to deal with two-way energy transfer, which may introduce technical issues.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] An over-voltage issue may come out as the electricity flows from these PV households back to the network.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] There are solutions to manage the over-voltage issue, such as regulating PV inverter power factor, new voltage and energy control equipment at electricity distributor level, re-conductor the electricity wires, demand side management, etc.
[src:solar-pv-systems/photovoltaics-p02] High generation during the middle of the day reduces the net generation demand, but higher peak net demand as the sun goes down can require rapid ramping of utility generating stations, producing a load profile called the duck curve.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] A **solar cell,** also known as a **photovoltaic cell** (**PV cell**), is an electronic device that converts the energy of light directly into electricity by using the photovoltaic effect.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] It is a type of photoelectric cell, a device whose electrical characteristics (such as current, voltage, or resistance) vary when it is exposed to light.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Individual solar cell devices are often the electrical building blocks of photovoltaic modules, known colloquially as "solar panels".
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Almost all commercial PV cells consist of crystalline silicon, with a market share of 95%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Cadmium telluride thin-film solar cells account for the remainder.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The common single-junction silicon solar cell can produce a maximum open-circuit voltage of approximately 0.5 to 0.6 volts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Photovoltaic cells may operate under sunlight or artificial light.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In addition to producing solar power, they can be used as a photodetector (for example infrared detectors), to detect light or other electromagnetic radiation near the visible light range, as well as to measure light intensity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] There are multiple input factors that affect the output power of solar cells, such as temperature, material properties, weather conditions, solar irradiance and more.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Arrays of solar cells are used to make solar modules that generate a usable amount of direct current (DC) from sunlight.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Strings of solar modules create a solar array to generate solar power using solar energy, many times using an inverter to convert the solar power to alternating current (AC).
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Electric vehicles that operate off of solar energy or sunlight are commonly referred to as solar cars.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] These vehicles use solar panels to convert absorbed light into electrical energy to be used by electric motors, with any excess energy stored in batteries.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Batteries in solar-powered vehicles differ from starting batteries in standard ICE cars because they are fashioned to impart power towards electrical components of the vehicle for a long durations.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The first instance of photovoltaic cells within vehicular applications was around midway through the second half of the 1900s.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In an effort to increase publicity and awareness in solar powered transportation Hans Tholstrup decided to set up the first edition of the World Solar Challenge in 1987.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] It was a 3000 km race across the Australian outback where competitors from industry research groups and top universities around the globe were invited to compete.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] General Motors ended up winning the event by a significant margin with their Sunraycer vehicle that achieved speeds of over 40 mph.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Contrary to popular belief, solar powered cars are one of the oldest alternative energy vehicles.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Multiple solar cells in an integrated group, all oriented in one plane, constitute a solar photovoltaic panel or module.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Photovoltaic modules often have a sheet of glass on the sun-facing side, allowing light to pass while protecting the semiconductor wafers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar cells connected in series creates an additive higher voltage, while connecting in parallel yields an additive higher current.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar modules can be interconnected to create an array with a desired peak DC voltage and loading current capacity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] This functionality can also be accomplished with various other solar devices that do more than just create the desired voltages and currents, such as with MPPTs (maximum power point trackers) or module level power electronic (MLPE) units: microinverters or DC-DC optimizers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Multiple solar cells assembled together in a single plane form a solar photovoltaic (PV) panel or module.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] These modules typically feature a glass sheet on the sun-facing side, which allows sunlight to pass through while safeguarding the semiconductor wafers from environmental factors.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Connecting solar cells in series increases the voltage output, whereas parallel connections enhance the current output.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar modules are often equipped with bypass diodes that isolate shaded cells, preventing them from affecting the performance of the entire string.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] These diodes allow the current to bypass the shaded or underperforming cells, thereby minimizing power loss and reducing the risk of damage.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] By 2020, the United States cost per watt for a utility scale system had declined to $0.94.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar cells were first used in a prominent application when they were proposed and flown on the Vanguard satellite in 1958, as an alternative power source to the primary battery power source.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] By adding cells to the outside of the body, the mission time could be extended with no major changes to the spacecraft or its power systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 1959 the United States launched Explorer 6, featuring large wing-shaped solar arrays, which became a common feature in satellites.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] These arrays consisted of 9600 Hoffman solar cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] By the 1960s, solar cells were (and still are) the main power source for most Earth orbiting satellites and a number of probes into the Solar System, since they offered the best power-to-weight ratio.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] State of the art technology implemented on satellites uses multi-junction photovoltaic cells, which are composed of different p–n junctions with varying bandgaps in order to utilize a wider spectrum of the Sun's energy.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Space solar cells additionally diverged from the protective layer used by terrestrial panels, with space applications using flexible laminate layers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Additionally, large satellites require the use of large solar arrays to produce electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] These solar arrays need to be broken down to fit in the geometric constraints of the launch vehicle the satellite travels on before being injected into orbit.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Historically, solar cells on satellites consisted of several small terrestrial panels folded together.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] These small panels would be unfolded into a large panel after the satellite is deployed in its orbit.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Newer satellites aim to use flexible rollable solar arrays that are very lightweight and can be packed into a very small volume.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The smaller size and weight of these flexible arrays drastically decreases the overall cost of launching a satellite due to the direct relationship between payload weight and launch cost of a launch vehicle.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 2020, the US Naval Research Laboratory conducted its first test of solar power generation in a satellite, the Photovoltaic Radio-frequency Antenna Module (PRAM) experiment aboard the Boeing X-37.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The photovoltaic effect was experimentally demonstrated first by French physicist Edmond Becquerel.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 1839, at age 19, he built the world's first photovoltaic cell in his father's laboratory.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Willoughby Smith first described the "Effect of Light on Selenium during the passage of an Electric Current" in a 20 February 1873 issue of Nature.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 1876 William Grylls Adams and Richard Evans Day constructed the first solid state photovoltaic cell.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 1883 Charles Fritts built another solid state photovoltaic cell by coating the semiconductor selenium with a thin layer of gold to form the junctions; the device was only around 1% efficient.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Pricing and efficiency Improvements were gradual over the 1960s.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] One reason that costs remained high was because space users were willing to pay for the best possible cells, leaving no reason to invest in lower-cost, less-efficient solutions.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Also, price was determined largely by the semiconductor industry; their move to integrated circuits in the 1960s led to the availability of larger boules at lower relative prices.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] As their price fell, the price of the resulting cells did as well.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] These effects lowered 1971 cell costs to some $100,000 per watt.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In late 1969 Elliot Berman joined Exxon's task force which was looking for projects 30 years in the future and in April 1973 he founded Solar Power Corporation (SPC), a wholly owned subsidiary of Exxon at that time.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The group concluded that electrical power would be much more expensive by 2000, and felt that the increase in price would make alternative energy sources more attractive.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] He conducted a market study and concluded that a price per watt of about $20/watt would create significant demand.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] By 1973 they announced a product, and SPC convinced Tideland Signal to use its panels to power navigational buoys, initially for the U.S.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Research into solar power for terrestrial applications became prominent with the U.S.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] National Science Foundation's Advanced Solar Energy Research and Development Division within the "Research Applied to National Needs" program, which ran from 1969 to 1977, and funded research on developing solar power for ground electrical power systems.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] A 1973 conference, the "Cherry Hill Conference", set forth the technology goals required to achieve this goal and outlined an ambitious project for achieving them, kicking off an applied research program that would be ongoing for several decades.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The program was eventually taken over by the Energy Research and Development Administration (ERDA), which was later merged into the U.S.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Following the 1973 oil crisis, oil companies used their higher profits to start (or buy) solar firms, and were for decades the largest producers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Exxon, ARCO, Shell, Amoco (later purchased by BP) and Mobil all had major solar divisions during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Technology companies also participated, including General Electric, Motorola, IBM, Tyco and RCA.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Adjusting for inflation, it cost $96 per watt for a solar module in the mid-1970s.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Process improvements and a very large boost in production have brought that figure down more than 99%, to 30¢ per watt in 2018 and as low as 20¢ per watt in 2020.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Swanson's law is an observation similar to Moore's Law that states that solar cell prices fall 20% for every doubling of industry capacity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] It was featured in an article in the British weekly newspaper The Economist in late 2012.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Balance of system costs are now higher than the solar panels alone, where in 2018 commercial arrays could be built at below $1.00 a watt, fully commissioned.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Sizes grew as surplus semiconductor equipment became available.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] ARCO Solar's original panels used cells 2 to 4 inches (50 to 100 mm) in diameter.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Panels in the 1990s and early 2000s generally used 125 mm wafers; since 2008, almost all new panels use greater than 156mm cells, and by 2020 even larger 182mm 'M10' cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Availability of large, high-quality glass sheets to cover the panels.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Widespread introduction of flat screen televisions in the late 1990s and early 2000s led to such availability.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] During the 1990s, polysilicon ("poly") cells became increasingly popular.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] These cells offer less efficiency than their mono-silicon ("mono") counterparts, but are grown in large vats that reduce cost.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] By the mid-2000s, poly was dominant in the low-cost panel market, but more recently the mono-silicon cells have returned to widespread use due to the efficiency gains.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Crystalline silicon panels dominate worldwide markets and are mostly manufactured in China and Taiwan.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] By late 2011, a drop in European demand dropped prices for crystalline solar modules to about $1.09 per watt down sharply from 2010.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Prices continued to fall in 2012, reaching $0.62/watt by 4Q2012.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] It was anticipated that electricity from PV will be competitive with wholesale electricity costs all across Europe and the energy payback time of crystalline silicon modules can be reduced to below 0.5 years by 2020.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Falling costs are considered one of the biggest factors in the rapid growth of renewable energy, of 2016, solar PV is growing fastest in Asia, with China and Japan currently accounting for half of worldwide deployment.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Costs of solar photovoltaic electricity fell by ~85% between 2010 (when solar and wind made up 1.7% of global electricity generation) and 2021 (where they made up 8.7%).
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Global installed PV capacity reached at least 301 gigawatts in 2016, and grew to supply 1.3% of global power by 2016.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 2019 solar cells accounted for ~3 % of the world's electricity generation at 720 Tw-hr.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar-specific feed-in tariffs vary by and within country countries.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Such tariffs can encourage the development of solar power projects and to achieve grid parity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Grid parity, the point at which photovoltaic electricity is equal to or cheaper than grid power without subsidies, is expected to be first achieved in areas with abundant sun and high electricity costs such as in California and Japan.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 2007 BP claimed grid parity for Hawaii and other islands that otherwise use diesel fuel to produce electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Bush set 2015 as the date for grid parity in the US.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The Photovoltaic Association reported in 2012 that Australia had reached grid parity (ignoring feed in tariffs).
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The price of solar panels fell steadily for 40 years, interrupted in 2004 when high subsidies in Germany drastically increased demand there and greatly increased the price of purified silicon (which is used in computer chips as well as solar panels).
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The Great Recession and the onset of Chinese manufacturing caused prices to resume their decline.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In the four years after January 2008 prices for solar modules in Germany dropped from €3 to €1 per peak watt.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] During that same time production capacity surged with an annual growth of more than 50%.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] China increased solar panel production market share from 8% in 2008 to over 55% in the last quarter of 2010.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In December 2012 the price of Chinese solar panels had dropped to $0.60/Wp (crystalline modules).
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] As of the end of 2016, it was reported that spot prices for assembled solar *panels* (not cells) had fallen to a record-low of US$0.36/Wp.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The second largest supplier, Canadian Solar Inc., had reported costs of US$0.37/Wp in the third quarter of 2016, having dropped $0.02 from the previous quarter, and hence was probably still at least breaking even.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Many producers expected costs would drop to the vicinity of $0.30 by the end of 2017.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] It was also reported that new solar installations were cheaper than coal-based thermal power plants in some regions of the world, and this was expected to be the case in most of the world within a decade.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] A solar cell is made of semiconducting materials, such as silicon, that have been fabricated into a p–n junction.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Such junctions are made by doping one side of the device p-type and the other n-type, for example in the case of silicon by introducing small concentrations of boron or phosphorus respectively.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar cells use "doping" of the silicon substrate to lower the activation energy thereby making the cell more efficient in converting photons to retrievable electrons.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Doping chemicals such as boron (p-type) are applied into the semiconductor crystal in order to create donor and acceptor energy levels substantially closer to the valence and conductor bands.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In operation, photons in sunlight hit the solar cell and are absorbed by the semiconductor.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] When the photons are absorbed, electrons are excited from the valence band to the conduction band (or from occupied to unoccupied molecular orbitals in the case of an organic solar cell), producing electron-hole pairs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] If the electron-hole pairs are created near the junction between p-type and n-type materials the local electric field sweeps them apart to opposite electrodes, producing an excess of electrons on one side and an excess of holes on the other.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The most commonly known solar cell is configured as a large-area p–n junction made from silicon.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Other possible solar cell types are organic solar cells, dye sensitized solar cells, perovskite solar cells, quantum dot solar cells, etc.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The illuminated side of a solar cell generally has a transparent conducting film for allowing light to enter into the active material and to collect the generated charge carriers.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Typically, films with high transmittance and high electrical conductance such as indium tin oxide, conducting polymers, or conducting nanowire networks are used for the purpose.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar cell efficiency may be broken down into reflectance efficiency, thermodynamic efficiency, charge carrier separation efficiency and conductive efficiency.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The overall efficiency is the product of these individual metrics.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The power conversion efficiency of a solar cell is a parameter which is defined by the fraction of incident power converted into electricity.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] A solar cell has a voltage dependent efficiency curve, temperature coefficients, and allowable shadow angles.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Due to the difficulty in measuring these parameters directly, other parameters are substituted: thermodynamic efficiency, quantum efficiency, integrated quantum efficiency, VOC ratio, and fill factor.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Reflectance losses are a portion of quantum efficiency under "external quantum efficiency".
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Recombination losses make up another portion of quantum efficiency, VOC ratio, and fill factor.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Resistive losses are predominantly categorized under fill factor, but also make up minor portions of quantum efficiency, VOC ratio.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The *fill factor* is the ratio of the actual maximum obtainable power to the product of the open-circuit voltage and short-circuit current.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] This is a key parameter in evaluating performance.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 2009, typical commercial solar cells had a fill factor > 0.70.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Grade B cells were usually between 0.4 and 0.7.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Cells with a high fill factor have a low equivalent series resistance and a high equivalent shunt resistance, so less of the current produced by the cell is dissipated in internal losses.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Single p–n junction crystalline silicon devices are now approaching the theoretical limiting power efficiency of 33.16%, noted as the Shockley–Queisser limit in 1961.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In the extreme, with an infinite number of layers, the corresponding limit is 86% using concentrated sunlight.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 2014, three companies broke the record of 25.6% for a silicon solar cell.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The company moved the front contacts to the rear of the panel, eliminating shaded areas.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In addition they applied thin silicon films to the (high quality silicon) wafer's front and back to eliminate defects at or near the wafer surface.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 2015, a 4-junction GaInP/GaAs//GaInAsP/GaInAs solar cell achieved a new laboratory record efficiency of 46.1% (concentration ratio of sunlight = 312) in a French-German collaboration between the Fraunhofer Institute for Solar Energy Systems (Fraunhofer ISE), CEA-LETI and SOITEC.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In September 2015, Fraunhofer ISE announced the achievement of an efficiency above 20% for epitaxial wafer cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The work on optimizing the atmospheric-pressure chemical vapor deposition (APCVD) in-line production chain was done in collaboration with NexWafe GmbH, a company spun off from Fraunhofer ISE to commercialize production.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] For triple-junction thin-film solar cells, the world record is 13.6%, set in June 2015.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 2016, researchers at Fraunhofer ISE announced a GaInP/GaAs/Si triple-junction solar cell with two terminals reaching 30.2% efficiency without concentration.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In 2017, a team of researchers at National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL), EPFL and CSEM (Switzerland) reported record one-sun efficiencies of 32.8% for dual-junction GaInP/GaAs solar cell devices.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In addition, the dual-junction device was mechanically stacked with a Si solar cell, to achieve a record one-sun efficiency of 35.9% for triple-junction solar cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar cells are typically named after the semiconducting material of which they are composed.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] These materials have varying characteristics to absorb optimal available sunlight spectrum.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Some cells are designed to handle sunlight that reaches the Earth's surface, while others are optimized for use in space.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar cells can be made of a single layer of light-absorbing material (single-junction) or use multiple physical configurations (multi-junctions) to take advantage of various absorption and charge separation mechanisms.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Second generation cells are thin film solar cells, that include amorphous silicon, CdTe and CIGS cells and are commercially significant in utility-scale photovoltaic power stations, building integrated photovoltaics or in small stand-alone power system.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Third generation of solar cells includes a number of thin-film technologies often described as emerging photovoltaics—most of them have not yet been commercially applied and are still in the research or development phase.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Many use organic materials, often organometallic compounds as well as inorganic substances.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Despite the fact that their efficiencies had been low and the stability of the absorber material was often too short for commercial applications, there is research into these technologies as they promise to achieve the goal of producing low-cost, high-efficiency solar cells.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] As of 2016, the most popular and efficient solar cells were those made from thin wafers of silicon which are also the oldest solar cell technology.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] By far, the most prevalent bulk material for solar cells is crystalline silicon (c-Si), also known as "solar grade silicon".
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Bulk silicon is separated into multiple categories according to crystallinity and crystal size in the resulting ingot, ribbon or wafer.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] These cells are entirely based around the concept of a p–n junction.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar cells made of c-Si are made from wafers between 160 and 240 micrometers thick.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Monocrystalline silicon (mono-Si) solar cells feature a single-crystal composition that enables electrons to move more freely than in a multi-crystal configuration.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Consequently, monocrystalline solar panels deliver a higher efficiency than their multicrystalline counterparts.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The corners of the cells look clipped, like an octagon, because the wafer material is cut from cylindrical ingots, that are typically grown by the Czochralski process.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar panels using mono-Si cells display a distinctive pattern of small white diamonds.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Solar cells made with this "kerfless" technique can have efficiencies approaching those of wafer-cut cells, but at appreciably lower cost if the CVD can be done at atmospheric pressure in a high-throughput inline process.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The surface of epitaxial wafers may be textured to enhance light absorption.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] In June 2015, it was reported that heterojunction solar cells grown epitaxially on n-type monocrystalline silicon wafers had reached an efficiency of 22.5% over a total cell area of 243.4 cm $^{2}$ .
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Heterojunction solar cells reached mass-production some time before 2022.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] It had also overtaken aluminum-back surface field (Al-BSF) panels in market share.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] However, it is not expected to outgrow conventional TOPCon (Tunnel Oxide Passivated Contact) due to similar theoretical efficiency ceilings and higher production costs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Polycrystalline silicon, or multicrystalline silicon (multi-Si) cells are made from cast square ingots—large blocks of molten silicon carefully cooled and solidified.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] They consist of small crystals giving the material its typical metal flake effect.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Polysilicon cells are the most common type used in photovoltaics and are less expensive, but also less efficient, than those made from monocrystalline silicon.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Ribbon silicon is a type of polycrystalline silicon—it is formed by drawing flat thin films from molten silicon and results in a polycrystalline structure.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] These cells are cheaper to make than multi-Si, due to a great reduction in silicon waste, as this approach does not require sawing from ingots.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] This form was developed in the 2000s and introduced commercially around 2009.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Also called cast-mono, this design uses polycrystalline casting chambers with small "seeds" of mono material.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The result is a bulk mono-like material that is polycrystalline around the outsides.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] When sliced for processing, the inner sections are high-efficiency mono-like cells (but square instead of "clipped"), while the outer edges are sold as conventional poly.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] This production method results in mono-like cells at poly-like prices.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Thin-film technologies reduce the amount of active material in a cell.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Most designs sandwich active material between two panes of glass.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Since silicon solar panels only use one pane of glass, thin film panels are approximately twice as heavy as crystalline silicon panels, although they have a smaller ecological impact (determined from life cycle analysis).
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] Cadmium telluride is the only thin film material so far to rival crystalline silicon in cost/watt.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] However cadmium is highly toxic and tellurium (anion: "telluride") supplies are limited.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] The cadmium present in the cells would be toxic if released.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] However, release is impossible during normal operation of the cells and is unlikely during fires in residential roofs.
[src:solar-pv-systems/solar-cell-p01] A square meter of CdTe contains approximately the same amount of Cd as a single C cell nickel-cadmium battery, in a more stable and less soluble form.
